fields.title: ElRubius
fields.overview: In this Spanish name, the first or paternal surname is Doblas and the second or maternal family name is Gundersen.
fields.body:
Elrubius Carrer

Ruben Doblus Gundersen (born 13 Feb 1990) professionally known as El Rubius is a Spanish-Norwegian (Spanish Father and Norwegian Mother) YouTuber. Primarily his Youtube channel consists of gameplays and vlogs. His Youtube channel is the 36th most subscribed Youtube channel in the world.

El Rubius also became the most subscribed YouTube channel in the country of Spain. In 2016 one of his tweets was the most retweeted in the world with 1.3 million retweets. He posted his first video in 2006 and became a full-time YouTuber in 2011. He also operates the YouTube channel ElRubiusOMG which he created in 2011. His content includes game playing, vlogs, channels, and more.

In 2011, his channel started popular in many Spanish countries. He gained attention when he posted the gameplay of Scrolls V: Skyrim. Later, he published lots of videos of him and gained a larger following. In 2012, he released his single “Minero”, which quickly became viral and became ElRubiusOMG’s most viewed video.

In November 2012, he became the most subscribed Spanish channel. After that in Feb 2015, he became the first Spanish YouTuber with 10 million subscribers. He published the interactive book The Troll Book in 2014. El Rubius won the YouTuber of the Year award in 2016 at the 1st Play Awards. In July 2018 he reached 30 million subscribers and in October 2015, he got the Diamond Play Button at the YouTube 10th Anniversary Party in Madrid.

On March 25, 2018, El Rubius broke Ninja and Drake’s record for most concurrent viewers during a Fortnite stream.

On July 15, 2020, Elrubius announced that he would stay on Twitch.

Ruben Doblas Gunderson known by his pseudonym elrubiusOMG or EI Rubius hails as a YouTube star and social media personality. His incredible work and affluence led him to be named as the YouTuber of the Year in 2016. With over 22 million subscribers in his channel sky is the limit. He is vastly known for his gameplays, tours, challenges and broad array of questions. In partnership with his best friend called Miguel Angel, the two have taken hold of online application around the globe. In fact his channel rockets as the most subscribed in Spain. This is what made him be crowned as YouTube star. To date, he has over 6 billion views and over 700 videos. Aside from his YouTube channel, he is also active on other accounts such as Instagram where he holds 5 million followers. His fans and viewers just can’t get enough of him

Childhood And Teenage Life

Born as Ruben Doblas Gundersen, he was first seen in the world on 13th, February 1990 in Mijas Spain. His father is a Spanish descent while his mother is a Norwegian. It was at his tender age that his parents parted ways. This forced him to move to Norway, but he currently resides in Spain, Madrid.

His zest for social media made him meet Miguel, and the rest is history as they say. They have come to rule the social media world by storm. While still at school, Rubius did a wide array of jobs hence turning him into an active lad. He is quite vast when it comes to speaking in English, Norwegian and Spanish.

Rise To Stardom

Rubius and Miguel encouraged each other to open their social accounts. But Miguel inspired El to try it out. It was here that he opted to start a YouTube Chanel. Miguel chipped in as a helper where the two chose to share their jokes on the said platform. It was in 2006 where Rubius opted to upload his first video under a moniker called Rubius. After some time he came up with his second channel titled as ElrubiusOMG in 2011.It was here that he took extra time to upload a wide array of gameplay videos especially The Elder Strolls which rose him to fame. Ceasing was something that Rubius didn’t include in his dictionary. By 2013 he had over a million of subscribers.

With massive of followers and fans on his side, Rubius opted to create other accounts. He first started with a six-minute video application called Vlog followed by Instagram account. In 2014 he authored a book titled The Troll Book. It was the same year that his book was declared as the bestselling piece at the Madrid Book Fair. In the mid of 2015, he authored a comic book called ElRubius. It is a superhero book that inspired him to venture into video games. His second section of the book is called Virtual Hero 2 followed by The Impossible Tower in 2016.As a multitalented persona, El starred in a movie called Torrente 5.

Is Rubius A Star?

Aside from his humoral moves and comic timing, Rubius comes with a unique and straightforward personality that is accepted by all. His zest for greatness makes him surpass all Vloggers and YouTuber stars. There is no doubt that he is the game-changer when it comes to social media sensation. Though competition seems to have been its ultimate failure, he distinguished himself as the ultimate choice. His originality and simplicity allowed him to be an all-time favorite.

I can fully attest that Rubius is a star in the making. His enthusiasm has attracted young audiences to subscribe to his channel. Unlike other YouTubers, Rubius perfectly knows his path and what his subscribers and followers want. For this reason, quantity isn’t part of his entertainment, but quality rules his world. His videos are well illustrated with high-quality content that makes one view continuously. He is not a vagabond or a hobo when it comes to stardom. In fact, he is the real definition of a principal performer.

Rubius Major Works

Though he is granted as the greatest personality, Rubius has already welcomed himself into the world of fame. Aside from him sharing tons of information online, little is known about his personal life. There is no doubt that he loves to play video games to the brim and he loves to spend time with his cat, Kitty. His favorite color is green, and his all-time dessert is chocolate ice cream. When it comes to his love life, Rubius doesn’t seem to have a lover.

fields.title: Philza
fields.overview: Philza is a seasoned Minecraft player and an avid streamer on both Twitch and YouTube. Aged 33, he holds a British nationality and has garnered more than a couple million followers along with over 20 million views in total as well.
fields.body:
Philza Career

Phil’s most popular video on YouTube is the one where he has created a montage of five years of playing Minecraft.

Usually, his Twitch streams are concerned with him playing the Minecraft hardcore survival. Phil even streams regularly during major events such as the Minecraft championships

On the other hand, his YouTube videos contain the edited highlights from his Twitch streams. From time to time, he uploads these highlights and has attracted close to 2.3 million followers on his YouTube channel over the years.

From multiple sources, Phil’s channels get about 500,000 views daily. Altogether, they manage to generate revenues worth $4000 per day for him, which are mainly driven by the advertisements from his channel.

Overall, Phil’s current net worth stands at about $2 million currently.
Even if a small number of viewers tune in to his channel, Phil continues to stream Minecraft often.

Currently, he has about four hardcore worlds in the aforementioned game. Three of these series’ have taken place from 2019 itself, whereas the first one dates back to 2012-13.
However, the most popular of them amongst the Minecraft community is the second series in which Phil built many things, including the Chaos Caverns.

Series 4 is going on even now, and it began merely five minutes following the conclusion of the preceding series.
Moreover, Phil consistently participates in the major group events that also include other Minecraft YouTubers.

He has also gone on to become a member of the Dream SMP. One of his latest moves has been to stream the progress that he makes on his newest hardcore world on Minecraft about four times a week on Twitch.

fields.title: Wilbur Soot
fields.overview: Will Gold popular as Wilbur Soot is a British Twitch streamer, singer, songwriter, and Youtuber. He gained popularity on Twitch and Youtube for streaming games like Minecraft, Sandbox and prank, reaction, and music videos. Further, he released his first single “The Nice Guy’ Ballad” in 2018 which has received several million views on social media platforms.
fields.body:
Wilbur Soot Carrer

Wilbur was born and raised in Suffolk, England along with his parents and siblings. He gained initial fame after being featured on a comedy channel “Soothouse” in a comedy video. In 2019, he created his self-titled channel and began streaming games like Sandbox and Minecraft. Within a short period, his videos went viral on social media and gave him millions of subscribers.

Will Gold popular as Wilbur Soot is a British Twitch streamer, singer, songwriter, and Youtuber. He gained popularity on Twitch and Youtube for streaming games like Minecraft, Sandbox, prank, reaction, and music videos. Further, he released his first single “The Nice Guy’s Ballad” in 2018 which has received several million views on social media platforms.

Wilbur was born and raised in Suffolk, England along with his parents and siblings. He gained initial fame after being featured on a comedy channel “Soothouse” in a comedy video. In 2019, he created his self-titled channel and began streaming games like Sandbox and Minecraft. Within a short period, his videos went viral on social media and gave him millions of subscribers.

Wilbur Soot Early Life

Wilbur was born in Suffolk, England on September 14, 1996, but he grew up in Brighton, East Sussex. He attended Sussex Downs College in Lewes, England, and recently finished a Bachelor’s degree in Editing and Post Production.

One of the first channels Wilbur had was named “Settings66” with a boy named Ben near Ipswich, Suffolk, East of England. The first video dates back to May 6, 2008. It consists of many IRL videos of the two boys seemingly acting out roleplay scenarios, and even two gaming walk-throughs. Wilbur claims that he doesn’t know the password to this account, and if he did, he would delete every video on this youtube channel, because it’s embarrassing to him, he claims.

He also owned a channel called “Minecraft and Donuts” (formerly 1MinecraftHD) with a girl named Sophie. The duo made Minecraft videos on player-made maps. Their first video, “Doll test Minecraft part 1,” was posted on May 22, 2011. They uploaded consistently until “Will and Sophie play: The Works | Part 2,” when Sophie had to go to the hospital to have an operation. Subsequently, they stopped uploading for 2 years. In “I'm BACK! +An Apology,” Will stated that she was fine but would not appear in videos anymore. However, he never uploaded on the channel again, and in late 2020, every video in it was private but more than half of the videos were private.

Another channel of his was named “ALittleBritOfWill” where he posted short films, music, and vlogs.

Wilbur Soot Career and Achievements

Will Gold popular as Wilbur Soot is a British Twitch streamer, singer, songwriter, and Youtuber. He gained popularity on Twitch and Youtube for streaming games like Minecraft, Sandbox, prank, reaction, and music videos. Further, he released his first single “The Nice Guy’s Ballad” in 2018 which has received several million views on social media platforms.

Wilbur was born and raised in Suffolk, England along with his parents and siblings. He gained initial fame after being featured on a comedy channel “Soothouse” in a comedy video. In 2019, he created his self-titled channel and began streaming games like Sandbox and Minecraft. Within a short period, his videos went viral on social media and gave him millions of subscribers.

Wilbur Soot Music Career

In addition to gaming and streaming, Wilbur is a popular musician, who has released a popular single in 2018 “The ‘Nice Guy’ Ballad”. As of now, the song has listened to millions of times. In 2019, he released famous singles such as “Maybe I Was Boring”, “I Am Very Smart”, and “Karen, Please Come Back I Miss The Kids”.

Wilbur’s song “Your New Boyfriend” of 2020 was recorded 10th in the UK Indie chart and 65th rank in UK Singles Chart. He has also released two EPs Maybe I Was Boring (2019) and Your City Gave Me Asthma (2020).

Wilbur is also one of the founding members of the popular music band “Lovejoy” along with his friends Joe Goldsmith, Mark Boardman, and Ash Kabosu. The band released its first EP “Are You Alright?” in 2021. They are going to release their first album at the end of this year.

Wilbur Soot and SMPEarth

SMP Earth is a server set up by Wilbur, JoshA20, chippledipple, and a few others. It is a 1:3000 scale map of the Earth with 75+ creators. In the server, people can own countries and claim land for that country. Creators role play with other creators and forge alliances or make enemies.

The server was not Wilbur’s idea but was already in development, However, the team had decided to abandon the project, thinking nobody would want to play on the server. Wilbur, having heard this, decided to step in and offered to lead the project himself, seeing the potential in the idea.

The server is now up and running, and has a wiki documenting the events that have taken place so far. Wilbur is the founder and leader of the SMP Earth faction known as Newfoundland. He has created a railway system connecting his land to other sections of the map, and refers to himself as a “social butterfly”.

Wilbur Soot Net Worth

Wilbur Soot is a popular content creator from the United Kingdom whose real name is Will Gold. He has an estimated net worth of $1.2 million. His content is mainly composed of parody songs and gaming videos of popular games like Among Us, Minecraft, etc. In addition to that, he also does meme reaction videos from time to time.

His youtube channel has over 5.6 million subscribers as of 2021 and has accumulated over 400 million views so far. It can get an average of 900,000 views per day from different sources. This should generate an estimated revenue of $4,500 ($1.6 million a year) from the ads that appear on the videos.

The streamer has over 3.7 million followers on Twitch and has accumulated over 6 million views so far. He can get an average viewership of 17,000 per stream with his highest viewership hitting 112,000 viewers. Streamers generally make money through subscribers, ad revenue, donations, and bits. Wilbursoot has an estimated 5,800 subscribers from whom he makes a minimum of $2.5 per month each. This revenue stream should generate an estimated $14,500 per month ($174,000 a year).

fields.title: Tyler1
fields.overview: Tyler1 is a 26-years-old American streamer and content creator. He is known for playing League of Legends gameplays.
fields.body:
Tyler1 Carrer

Before Tyler Steinkamp became the man we know him to be today, he was a Computer Science major at Central Methodist University where he was a part of the school’s football team. In the middle of his studies at the University, Tyler suddenly dropped out of school to pursue a career in streaming games online in League of Legends.

Even before he started streaming, Tyler was already a well-established player who was among the top players in higher elos. He was a Draven one-trick who would play the champion in every lane he could and was among the very few players at the time to successfully execute the champion well. Tyler became famous for his antics on screen but to become a famous streamer, you had to push for more to gain more viewers.

The first signs of fame came in 2014 when he attracted the attention of some fans as he peaked 13th on NA's competitive ladder. At the time, he was mostly playing ADC, preferably Draven, a pick that will become a signature champion of his in the years to come. That being said, his career didn\'t take off until 2016, when he decided to withdraw from Central Methodist University and fully focus on his League of Legends career as a content creator and high ELO player.

Streaming Career

If you were an original viewer of Tyler’s streams, you knew what kind of content you were getting into. When it comes to toxicity, Tyler1 was the very definition of what that word meant in the gaming community. He was a League of Legends streamer who would feature his gameplay primary when he was on Draven, but when he didn’t get his champion every one on his team would suffer the consequences of not giving him what he wants.

Tyler1 was known to intentionally feed kills to the enemy team by running straight into the tower. He would also flame his team whenever some of them would underperform. Tyler’s temper was his most charming factor where he would destroy your earphones by screaming into the microphone to try and get his point across. The worst part about that is people found it funny so his channel grew bigger and bigger.

Tyler1's initial spike in popularity came from viral short clips in which he\'d insult his teammates or intentionally lose games. He had a so-called \"int list\" at the time, which was a list of players that he would troll and intentionally lose games with if he played with them on the team. He had broad descriptions of those players he hated, the reasons why he hated them, and what he\'ll do if he encounters them in-game.

Riot Games didn’t have a strong system against cheaters and toxic players back then but they managed to punish Tyler1 in a way. Tyler would frequently get banned or suspended but since Tyler’s content was mainly on the entertainment factor he gave while being toxic, the bans wouldn’t faze him so he’d simply create a new account to climb the ladder again. He did so every time Riot Games banned his accounts and it didn’t bother him one bit. He stayed true to his identity even if his account was different each time.

Indefinite Ban From League

Now that Tyler had become one of League of Legends' most influential figures, Riot Games had no choice but to take action against him unless they wanted the players to know that players like him can get away with toxic behavior. For the first time in League of Legends history, Riot Games’ implemented an ID Ban. This ban was unique since it didn’t only ban an account you owned, it banned you – as the person – from the game.

Whenever Tyler1 would stream a game, his account would instantly get banned. Sure, Tyler could still play the game while he wasn’t streaming but that doesn’t earn him money at all. No matter how many accounts he created, Riot Games would snipe him off Twitch so that he could never share his gameplay live on the game ever again. At this point, he knew that there was no way Tyler could make money off League of Legends again.

From April 2016 to January 2018, Riot Games made it its mission to prevent Tyler from streaming League again. Unfortunately, Tyler1 managed to sneak in 1 or 2 games of League during his streams but would be banned immediately after. During this period, he would desperately cling to a streaming by trying out new games or showcasing a variety of streams such as cooking shows or discussions about random stuff or news.

The #FreeTyler1 Movement

When Tyler was permanently banned from League of Legends, it instigated a movement where his fans would ask for Riot Games to free him from his ban. During live esports events, people on the stage would lift sign cards that had the #FreeTyler1 hashtag written to show their support for their favorite streamer. There were even petitions only which supported the movement stating Riot Games should unban him from League of Legends.

Tyler became a martyr in the League of Legends community for all the players that have been banned before. It doesn’t make sense that someone who intentionally behaved in a toxic manner in form of tens of thousands of viewers. Although Riot Games saw how much the community saw Tyler as someone they looked up to so they devised a plan that would provide a huge impact on the League of Legends community

The Comeback To League

On January 4, 2018, Riot Games lifted the ban on Tyler1 after he claimed that he underwent intensive rehab to fix his toxic behavior on stream. During his first stream after a while, Tyler broke the record of having the highest amount of viewers in a single stream with over 386,000 viewers. This became one of the most momentous events in League of Legends history as one of the most hated people in the game finally achieved his grand return.

Tyler being reformed wasn’t just something he claimed to get Riot Games’ favor, though. Players tried to test Tyler’s patience by banning Draven on his streams or intentionally angering him but he kept his cool. The man would no longer go on aggressive sprees to display his dissatisfaction but would instead use the opportunity given to him by accepting losses with grace. Many people were disappointed with this change but even more, people started respecting Tyler and gained more viewers because of this.

Tyler still retained his image of being the overly masculine dude that screamed into the microphone. However, he only did this in the camera and not on the game’s chat system. It also wasn’t as severe or personal as it used to be and he would only get angry in acceptable cases that even normal people would get angry at. Overall, viewers and esports personalities started accepting this revamped version of the popular streamer in 2016.

Tyler1 Championship Series

Tyler’s welcome back to League of Legends was so huge that Riot Games even allowed him to sponsor his tournament where he, himself, would cast the games. It was met with a lot of support that popular streamers such as Imaqtipie, Scarra, Voyboy, Nightblu3, and Shiphtur even joined in on the fun to compete against other top players from all around North America. This would mark a major change in the streaming community.

League's Biggest Content Creator

The period after Tyler1's urban up until today is filled with many memorable moments, such as him getting Challenger on roles he hasn\'t previously touched, or him making TCS in both 2018 and 2019, awarding dedicated players with over $100.000 total.

That being said, there is one moment that specifically stands out in this period. The summer split LCS final in September 2019, in which Tyler1 played on Riot's stage alongside ex-pro players and other big League streamers alike. The game was watched live by millions at home and thousands in person, with the VOD of the game having almost 7 million views at the time of writing. The detail that perhaps stood out the most is that Tyler laned with Phreak, his former nemesis and current Riot employee, which made the game even more iconic than it already was.

It was the first time that Riot officially affiliated themselves with Tyler1, and the community was stoked to see Tyler on the big stage for the first time. It was one of the biggest moments in League of Legends history, as riot partnered up with the biggest content creator their game has to offer, despite his controversial past. Overall, it's an amazing redemption story of a random kid from Missouri that overcame his toxicity issues to become Riot's ambassador and one of the most beloved figures in the community of the world's biggest multiplayer game.

fields.title: Dream
fields.overview: Born in 1999, Dream grew up with an attention deficit hyperactivity disorder. He kicked off his first YouTube channel in 2014 but began uploading quality videos only five years later.
fields.body:
Dream Career

However, it can be argued that he had a knack for attracting followers towards him right from the very beginning. You see, Dream’s first proper video was of his playing Minecraft poorly, deliberately, as he wanted the content to get viral online.

The ploy worked to an extent too, as the video has garnered over 10 million views till date and is still going strong on the video streaming platform.

Interestingly, he titled the video ‘My Cursed Minecraft World’, and shot to fame quite instantly.

Though Dream’s Twitter account was suspended owing to some reasons, he is a popular figure amongst the gaming community on Instagram.

Moreover, he has several stints at YouTube since the last eight years, opening and wrapping up multiple accounts with different names.
However, as the great saying goes, every overnight success is a 20 years of hard-work in the making.

He was stuck at 1000 subscribers for five years until 2019, and looked all set to become yet another gamer struggling to come on terms with the cutting-edge competition that exists on the internet.
Yet, Clay, as he is known in his inner circle, managed to find his first breakthrough in 2019 and has never looked back ever since.
Dream caught the eye of the masses when he arranged a program to discover internet sensation PewDiePie’s Minecraft world seed at around the same time.

Though he does play many different games, Dream’s YouTube account is primarily concerned around his adventures in Minecraft. He was adequately rewarded for a promising 2019 by being nominated for the 10th annual Streamy awards in 2020.

As his popularity grew, Dream naturally looked for avenues to expand his forays and thus released a song featuring PmBata in February 2021.

Soon afterwards, riding on the success of the first song, Clay announced the release of his song on Twitter. However, that particular video has arguably not seen the light of the day yet.

Dream’s sudden rise to stardom has complemented his personal net worth as well, which stands at around $12 million currently. His YouTube videos have collected views over two billion so far, and has close to 30 million subscribers as well.
In addition to his total net worth, Clay also collects about $9 million annually from the advertisements through his YouTube videos.

fields.title: xChocoBars
fields.overview: Janet Rose known online by the moniker xChocoBars is a Twitch streamer and content creator. Janet is Canadian but currently resides in America. She was born in Toronto, Canada on 5th November 1994.
fields.body:
xChocoBars Career

She has an outspoken personality but is extremely reserved and shy when it comes to matters regarding her family. The names of her parents, siblings, and family relatives are currently unknown. She is known for streaming League Of Legends on her Twitch channel. Her gameplay is a treat to the eyes and she is mechanically skilled for the MOBA game. Her account has almost 400k followers and upwards of 12 million views.

Although not much is known about her childhood and early life, some records can be traced and gathered. She had previously tried to finish her studies and formal education from a school but eventually had to back out to pursue her career as an online personality. Around 2017 she informed her fans through a stream that her father had to undergo an emergency surgery in China and that he has recovered to a stable condition.

Janet began her online presence in the year 2013 when she created a Youtube channel. Her channel titled xChocoBars released its debut video in November of 2013. xChocoBar’s real claim to fame is her talent and passion for the game League Of Legends. She regularly streams on Twitch and uses her exceptional skills to outplay her opponents and create content for others to watch and learn from.

Janet has over 400k followers and 12 million views. She was a member of the diamond league during the LOL 2018 season. xChocobar was living in Los Angeles between 2018 and 2019 along with twitch streamer Celine, who is known online as Starsmitten. She is a Twitch partner and is also a part of LOL parter program with Riot Games.

Her sponsors include Tokyo Japan Crate who have partnered with her to create an online monthly subscription service. She also receives Japanese snacks, candies and drinks from a firm on a monthly basis.

Achievements

xChocobars started creating videos on Youtube in November of 2013 whereas she started Twitch in 2015. During the early days of her online career, she was most known for her gameplay and commentary on various games. League Of Legends, Fortnite, Teamfight Tactics are some of the games she enjoyed playing on her streams. Her fans are called the Potato Army.

Rose was also one of the four captains in the 100k LOL esports charity tournament. Alongside her starred other big names such as Pokimane, LilyPichu and Kaypea. She also played Fortnite with Josh Hart who is an NBA player in the IGN Fortnite Streamer Showdown.

Janet has also taken part in competitive esports when she placed first at Twitch Rivals: LOL tournament with team EZ Clap. She also participated in an Apex Legend’s tournament sponsored by ESPN. xChocobar was a finalist for the Twitch streamer of the year award at the 11th Shorty Awards.

She started streaming Among Us when it boosted in popularity in 2021.

Net Worth

xChocoBars is a sucessful Twitch streamer and internet celebrity from Toronto, Canada. Her real name is Janet Rose. She has an estimated net worth of around $1.1 million.

She has over 900k followers as of 2021 and has amassed more than 50 million views. This includes ad revenue, donations and subscription fees. All of this adds up to give an estimated net worth of around $90,000 a year. She makes a fair decent amount of money from other sponsors and avenues available to her.

fields.title: Loserfruit
fields.overview: Kathleen Belsten, more popularly known by her online alias ‘Loserfruit’, is an Australian internet celebrity best known for streaming video games on Twitch.
fields.body:
Loserfruit Career

She created her YouTube channel on March 24, 2013, where she started posting content about video games. Before becoming a full-time streamer, she used to work at the Australian Broadcasting Corporation.

Loserfruit started by streaming â€˜League of Legendsâ€™, and then went on to explore other popular games such as â€˜The Legend of Zelda: Majoraâ€™s Maskâ€™, and â€˜GoldenEye 007.â€™ She has also started streaming â€˜Call of Dutyâ€™, and â€˜Overwatch.â€™

This Australian social media personality rose to fame for her Overwatch and Fortnite videos which she started making in 2013. Since starting her YouTube channel, she has acquired more than 333 million lifetime views on her content.

By 2017, she had become extremely popular for her gaming skills. In addition to the earnings through subscriptions, ad revenue, and sponsorships, Loserfruit also gets remunerated through donations.

Loserfruit is a member of the Australian YouTuber collective ‘Click’ which also includes other stars like Bazza Gazza, Creator, LazarBeam, Mrfreshasian, Muselk, Prestige Clips, Tannar, and Mully. She has frequent collaborations with members of the â€˜Click Crew’.

Along with her primary YouTube account with millions of followers, Loserfruit also has a second channel called â€œLufuâ€ where she posts about her life such as living in the ‘Click House’ (the house owned by the Australian YouTuber group ‘Click’), traveling, and pranks. This channel chronicles her travels, in the form of vlogs, and features gameplay highlights. Loserfruit is also popular on other social media platforms such as Twitter and Instagram.

Along with her gaming skills, Loserfruit is also known for her genuine demeanor and subtle wit.

She made her television debut in 2014 when she appeared in the Australian version of the news-magazine show, â€˜60 Minutes’. Loserfruit is also featured as a voice actor on ‘Meta Runner’, a web series produced by Glitch Productions.

In 2020, Loserfruit developed a Fortnite skin which was released as a part of the Fortnite “Icon” series. Before this, gaming superstar Ninja had designed his Icon Series cosmetic. This makes Loserfruit only the second content creator to have her exclusive skin in Fortnite.

This year, she also launched her own Podcast on her YouTube channel titled â€œAll In.â€ She hosts this podcast along with Create. Topics discussed in this podcast include such things as dating other YouTubers, reading her private email, and much more.

Along with these, Loserfruit also announced that she would become an official athlete for the company GymShark, in the same year. Gymshark is a company selling athletic clothing which often partners with influencers.

Loserfruit has an estimated net worth of $1.5 million. The content mainly consists of gameplay videos of the popular battle royale game known as Fortnite. She adds an entertaining commentary to her gameplay videos which her fans enjoy. Aside from Fortnite, she also plays Minecraft from time to time.

Her Youtube channel has over 2 million subscribers as of 2021 and has accumulated over 280 million views so far. It can get an average of 150,000 views per day from different sources. This should generate an estimated revenue of $750 per day ($270,000 a year) from the ads that appear on the videos.

Loserfruit has over 1.1 million fruits on Twitch and has accumulated over 35 million views so far. She can get an average of 1,200 viewers per stream and her highest viewership hit around 6,000 viewers. Twitch streamers make money through ads, subscriptions, donations, and bits. Loserfruit has around 2,300 subscribers on the channel from which she makes a minimum of $2.5 per subscriber each month. This should be a total of $5,750 per month ($69,000 a year).

fields.title: Amouranth
fields.overview: Amouranth is an American Twitch streamer whose real name is Kaitlyn Michelle Siragusa. She is known to be an amazing cosplayer, erotic model and a Youtuber who also streams on Twitch.
fields.body:
Amouranth Career

She was born in Houston, Texas. She taught herself how to design costumes back in 2010 and went on to work at Houston Grand Opera and Houston Ballet as a costume designer. Currently, she is married to Nick Lee.

Amouranth began her online career as a cosplayer and costumier back in 2010. She created her own cosplays of popular gaming, comic book, and other pop culture characters. It didn’t take long before she was scouted by the Houston Grand Opera and Houston Ballet in Texas, US, her home state

Earlier in her career as a costume designer she worked for theatre companies and created clothing for ballet productions. She started her own character company for children’s entertainment in 2015. It has gained traction over the past few years and is a profitable business as of now. She has appeared on the famous TV show “The Little Couple” on Discovery network twice and has also been featured on local news stations.

All her success has garnered her a huge audience on Twitch with 3.6 million followers and often peaking at 16k concurrent viewers. In March of 2021 she overtook Pokimane as the most popular female Twitch streamer. She was one of the most paid streamers of 2021.

Popularity

She rose to popularity in 2016 when she started streaming on Twitch. She was known for her cosplaying and used her social media accounts to advertise her cosplaying career. She also made multiple appearances on different gaming and comic conventions.

She started streaming under the Creative category on Twitch, which was later renamed to Just Chatting. It was a category where streamers do not play games but instead spend their time interacting with their viewers. She has since then done a tremendous amount of streams on cooking, ASMR, animal streams and Just Chatting. Her real claim to fame came from Hot Tub streams. This included playing games in a hot tub while writing the names of the donors on her body.

Net Worth

Amouranth is a costume designer and model who lives in Houston Texas. Her real name is Kaitlyn Siragusa. She has an estimated net worth of around $7 million. She started her own character company for aimed towards children which is called A Charned Affair for children’s entertainment.

She has a huge following on Twitch with over 3.7 million followers. She makes her revenue from advertisements and donations from subscribers. This is estimated to be around $17000 considering she has around 6800 subscribers.

Apart from Twitch she gathers income from her Patreon account, where she makes around 15k a month and Onlyfans from which she nets around 100k a month.

fields.title: Sway
fields.overview: Faze Sway is a member of the Faze clan and a professional Fortnite player. He was previously a member of Chronic before he joined Faze in February of 2019. Sway also has a Youtube channel with millions of subscribers.
fields.body:
Sway Career

He usually posts gaming videos which sometimes include educational videos for the Fortnite community. Sway has a huge fanbase with his Fortnite gameplay and other gaming videos. He is mostly known for his Fortnite plays and streams. His real name is Josue Sway, but on social media, he is Faze Sway.

Josue is American by nationality but then moved to Mexico as per the Faze official webpage. He is brother to two younger sisters and has an older brother. The identity of Sway’s parents are currently unknown and there is very little information about his siblings. It can be confirmed that the passion for gaming struck early in the mind of Sway. His early Youtube videos show him playing vintage games like Call Of Duty. He was extremely passionate about shooters and developed great mechanical skills at an early age. When it comes to Fortnite he is a great builder and is known for his high ground retakes.

As of September 2021, Sway is 18 years old. He is Christian and of Puerto Rican descent although of American nationality. Sway celebrates his birthday on July 1.

Net Worth

Faze Sway has quite a huge following when it comes to all his social media accounts. He has over 4 million subscribers on Youtube, around 1.4 million followers on Twitter. When it comes to Instagram he boasts around 3.2 million followers. He does not seem to currently have a Twitch account, so no streaming revenue.

Sway begun playing games competitively at a young age and has made it big with Faze Clan. His Youtube channel was created back in 2013. His first video was posted on March of 2017 which was a Call Of Duty video. The video included extended gameplay and was titled “Easy De Atomizer”. The video has over 200,000 views as of now.

Sway’s channel has garnered over 420 million views throughout its existence. He posts frequently on his Youtube. Sway has an estimated net worth of around $5 million. His wealth mainly consists of his earnings from Youtube and a bunch of sponsorship deals. It is to be noted that he is under a contract to represent Faze Clan and is believed to be worth a good amount of money. He also has multiple paid promotions and endorsement deals on his Instagram handle, which generate decent money. His sponsors include big brands like G Fuel, Nissan, ScufGaming.

Controversies

Sway Losing Fortnite Support-A-Creator

Support-A-Creator code is a feature Fortnite introduced to help aid the content creators in the community with some financial help. A fraction of the money spent on V bucks goes to any creator of your choice based on the code you choose while making the transaction. However Faze Sway tweeted in July on 2021 that his creator code was permanently removed by the developers. He also posted a screenshot alongside the tweet which was from the developers indicating how he violated the terms of service.

However no details are mentioned from the developers on the issue. It is believed that Epic banned Sway because of his cryptic tweets towards Fortnite dying and the lack of new content. Fortnite is known to ban people because of their toxic comments on social media accounts targeted towards the developers and the game.

Accused Of Cheating And Teaming Up

Sway was competing in the Solo Cash Cup when he was accused of teaming up with Wistles. According to tournament guidelines provided by Epic, it is a bannable offence and against the rules to team up with other players. Sour provides video evidence which shows both of the players targeting him and then ignoring each other after his death.

Sour also said that there was no point in reporting Sway since he has a massive following. However, he was proved wrong as this made waves through the Fortnite community and Sway received tons of backlash while some even supported him. Sway later confirmed that he was on a phone call with his friends while competing in the tournament. He mentioned that he had no intent of sabotaging someone else’s game or teaming up. He did agree to ignore Wistle as he was a friend, which he apologized for.

fields.title: Adin Ross
fields.overview: Adin Ross was born and brought up in a Jewish household and spent a part of his childhood in New York City.
fields.body:
Adin Ross Career

Ross is known as an acquaintance of basketball legend LeBron James’ son Bronny. The duo had even bet several thousands of dollars on 2K games. This had also shot Ross to fame for the very first time.

From there on, he began hosting e-dates on his channel and that helped him expand his influence to videos not related to games as such.

Rapper Tee Grizzley too appeared on his channel as he coupled with Ross to play GTA on his channel.

Ross also streamed a video from a hot water tub with fellow Twitch streamer Corinna Kapf. Many people went on to follow Ross after that video and the streamer’s prominence in the community has been on the rise since then.

He has collaborated with other personalities such as ZIAS, B-Lou, Lil Tecca, Lil Tjay, Iann Dior and 24KGoldn amongst others so far.
Adin Ross’ persona is defined as ‘infectious’, and he tends to rub shoulders with some very popular people who are closely tracked on platforms like Twitch, YouTube and even the tabloids!

Adin has also been engaging in the celebrity boxing segment recently as he challenged influencer FlightReacts for a fight recently.

So far, he has raised a net worth of over $2 million and last year his YouTube channel hit subscribers of around 1.3 million as well.

In total, his videos’ views have shot up over 20 million so far and each stream of his attracts around 36,000 views on an average.

Each of Ross’ subscribers contributes about $2.5 individually to his kitty and he tends to bag around $45,000 annually via advertisements, donations, subscriptions as well. Certainly to say, Adin Ross is someone whose graph is on the rise and a gamer-streamer-influencer to watch out for in the future.

fields.title: Ninja
fields.overview: Tyler “Ninja” Blevins is an American Fortnite streamer who is currently under contract to Luminosity Gaming.
fields.body:
Ninja Career

Richard Tyler Blevins professionally named as Alias Ninja born on June 5,1991 is an American Streamer, YouTuber, Professional gamer and Internet personality.

Blevins started his career in gaming and streaming by participating in several esports teams for Halo. He began playing professionally in 2009. He played for various organization like Cloud9, Renegades, Team Liquid and Luminosity Gaming. Blevins started playing H1Z1 and then PlayerUnknown’s Battelgrounds. After H1Z1 , he started playing PUBG and won PUBG Gamescom Invitational Squads classification in August 2017. But his popularity increased by playing Fortnite Battle Royale in october 2017. His viewership started growing and his followers on Twitch had grown from 500,000 in September 2017 to over 2 million by March 2018. Blevin set the Twitch record for the largest concurrent audience.

In 2016, he moved on H1Z1 and then started playing PUBG.

Ninja has a net worth of $7 million dollars according to Naibuzz. His primary YouTube channel has more than 6.5 billion views and 29 million subscribers which made him the 4th most subscribed channel as well as the 2nd most subscribed Spanish language channel.

Esports and streaming

Blevins began playing Halo 3 professionally in 2009. He played for various organizations including Cloud9, Renegades, Team Liquid, and most recently, Luminosity Gaming. Blevins became a streamer in 2011. He began playing H1Z1, then moved to PlayerUnknown’s Battlegrounds. He joined Luminosity Gaming in 2017 first as a Halo player, then to H1Z1, later moving to PUBG, where he won the PUBG Gamescom Invitational Squads classification in August 2017.

Blevins began streaming the newly released Fortnite Battle Royale shortly after the PUBG Gamescom Invitational. His viewership began to grow, which coincided with the game’s growth in popularity over the late 2017/early 2018 period. His followers on Twitch had grown from 500,000 in September 2017 to over 2 million by March 2018.

In March 2018, Blevins set the Twitch record for the largest concurrent audience on an individual stream (outside of tournament events), 635,000, while playing Fortnite with Drake, Travis Scott, and Juju Smith-Schuster. This stream inspired Epic Games, the developers behind Fortnite, to host a charitable pro-am event featuring popular streamers like Blevins paired with famous celebrities in Fortnite at E3 2018 in June of that year; Blevins paired with electronic musician Marshmello won the event. In April 2018, he broke his own viewing record during his event Ninja Vegas 2018, where he accumulated an audience of about 667,000 live viewers.

Blevins partnered with Red Bull Esports in June 2018, and held a special Fortnite event, the Red Bull Rise Till Dawn in Chicago on July 21, 2018, where players could challenge him.

Blevins’ rise in popularity on Twitch is considered to be synergistically tied to the success of Fortnite Battle Royale. In December 2018, Blevins estimated he had made close to US$10 million in 2018, while Epic Games reported they had earned over US$3 billion in revenue in the year, primarily due to Fortnite. To acknowledge’s Blevins’ importance to Fortnite’s success, Epic added a Ninja-based cosmetic skin to the game in January 2020 as the first part of an “Icon Series” for other real-life personalities associated with Fortnite.

Reuters reported that Blevins had been paid US$1 million by Electronic Arts to promote Apex Legends, a competing battle royale game to Fortnite, for playing the game on his Twitch stream and promoting the title through social media account during Apex release in February 2019.

On August 1, 2019, Blevins left Twitch to stream exclusively on Microsoft’s Mixer platform. His wife and manager Jessica told The Verge that the contract with Twitch had limited the ability for Ninja to grow his brand outside of video gaming, and that because of the state of Twitch’s community, “it really seemed like he was kind of losing himself and his love for streaming.

In addition to large number of subscribers on Twitch and Mixer, Blevins has over 23 million subscribers on YouTube as of May 2020. At the time, he was earning over $500,000 per month from streaming Fortnite and credits the game’s free-to-play business model as a growth factor.

Due to the shutdown of Mixer in July 2020, Blevins was released from his exclusivity deal, enabling him to stream on other platforms.On July 8, 2020, Blevins began streaming on YouTube.

Other appearances

Blevins and his family were featured in several episodes of the television game show Family Feud in 2015, while he was gaining popularity as a professional video game player. According to The Brillion News, Blevins was the reason he and his team were able to make it onto the show. In an episode aired August 2019, after he had achieved his fame, his family returned as contestants on Celebrity Family Feud.

In September 2018, Blevins became the first professional esports player to be featured on the cover of ESPN The Magazine, marking a breakthrough into mainstream sports fame.

Blevins worked with the record label Astralwerks in October 2018 to compile an album titled Ninjawerks: Vol. 1 featuring original songs by electronic music acts including Alesso, Nero, Tycho, and 3LAU. Blevins, in addition to being fans of these artists, felt the album was “another big step towards bridging the gap between music artists and gamers”. The album was released on December 14, 2018.

Blevins was one of several Internet celebrities featured in YouTube Rewind 2018: Everyone Controls Rewind, which also heavily featured Fortnite. Blevins appeared briefly during the NFL’s “The 100-Year Game” ad alongside numerous several professional football players that aired during Super Bowl LIII in 2019. He was the only participant in the commercial with no ties whatsoever to football in any form.

On August 20, 2019, Blevins’ book Get Good: My Ultimate Guide to Gaming was published by Penguin Random House.

Ninja Charitable work

In a fundraising charity stream held in February 2018, Blevins raised over $110,000 to be donated to the American Foundation for Suicide Prevention. During the first Fortnite Battle Royale Esports event in April 2018, Blevins gave away nearly $50,000 in prize money, with $2,500 of that going to the Alzheimer’s Association. Later in April, he participated in the #Clips4Kids event with other fellow streamers DrLupo and TimTheTatman, and in total, he helped raise over $340,000. At E3 2018, Blevins and Marshmello won the Fortnite Pro-Am event which resulted in the donation of the $1 million prize to a charity of their choice.

Ninja Controversies

Blevins has stated that he does not stream with female gamers out of respect for his wife and to avoid the rumors that such streaming could create. He received mixed reactions; some said that he should set an example and not make it more difficult for female streamers to rise to prominence, while others supported his stance, claiming that he should be allowed to do what he wants to protect his marriage. In response to his critics, Blevins has reaffirmed his support for gender equality and restated his commitment to his marriage, and mentioned some prominent female streamers by name. He has also made clear that women are welcome to play with him in a group or at events, saying that such situations allow him to “control the narrative more, without stupid drama and rumors flooding into our lives.

In December 2016, Blevins released the address of a donor as retribution for having a racist screen name and donation message. This act, which is referred to as “doxing”, is against the Twitch rules, which states they can result in an “indefinite suspension”. Blevins was reported for this act, but only received a 48-hour suspension, which some believed was a result of Blevins’ large audience on the platform. Blevins later tweeted that he deserved the punishment.

In March 2018, while in a stream with Nadeshot, Blevins improvised the word “nigga” while rapping to Logic’s “44 More”. This sparked controversy within his watching community and the general public. He later apologized for any offense caused and stated that he did not intend to say the word, instead attributing his use of the word to being “tongue-tied”.

In October 2018, Blevins reported a player for “having a higher ping” than him. This led to a player claiming on November 16, 2018, that they had been banned as a result of the report, which Epic Games denied. Both of these incidents caused backlash against Blevins on social media.

In November 2018, Blevins received criticism for falsely reporting IcyFive, a Fortnite player, for stream sniping. After Blevins was eliminated by IcyFive, Blevins’ teammate, DrLupo, told him to watch for an “emote”, which IcyFive did perform. Blevins took this as proof that IcyFive was stream sniping and quickly reported the player. After reporting IcyFive, Blevins stated that he would “go out of his way” to ensure IcyFive got banned and told IcyFive that he would not report him if he left the game immediately despite already having reported him. As IcyFive was not viewing the stream, he did not do so. Blevins assumed IcyFive was ignoring him and took out his phone in what appeared to be an attempt at directly contacting Epic Games. IcyFive claimed that he did not stream snipe Blevins and uploaded a video as proof. DrLupo later stated that he did not believe IcyFive stream sniped Blevins, mentioning that using an emote was a regular reaction to an increase in spectator count after elimination, and also stated that he did not condone Blevins’ actions, comparing them to a rant. Blevins later apologized to IcyFive on Twitter but also accused the player of “playing the victim” and “milking” the incident, calling him “naive” for assuming players would be banned solely on his word.

fields.title: Ranboo
fields.overview: He had risen to fame only recently, having opened his YouTube channel in January 2020. However, Ranboo didn’t even post his first video over there until the August of that year, in which he is seen playing skywars.
fields.body:
Ranboo Career

However, this ploy also seems to be a bait of sorts given that he has vowed to do a complete face reveal after hitting 5 million subscribers on his channel.

Ranboo also seems to have some interest in cooking given that his most popular video on Twitter is the one where he bakes an entire cake for the audience.

Clips of the video went pretty viral on Tiktok and he instantly gained about 5000 subscribers on YouTube as well.

Ranboo seemed to be using some random gimmicks to gain traction, given that he revealed in a stream that he would be contesting for the president of a Dream SMP nation L’Manberg!

Yet, the strategy seemed to be working properly as he garnered over a million subscribers on the first anniversary of his YouTube channel.

By introducing a new tech feature Ranboo even became the second-most subscribed Twitch user of all time for a brief period last year.

He also raised over $100,000 for the Trevor Project, a charity stream, which went on for more than 10 hours on Twitch.
Moreover, he attracted about 45000 new subscribers during that session. He was also gifted several thousands of subscribers at that time, with Dream SMP itself contributing with 1000 subscribers on their own.

Ranboo broke the glass ceiling multiple times last year, even becoming the youngest-ever streamer to hit the top rank in Twitch’s charts. He ensures that his content is available across platforms, as Ranboo uploads content on his YouTube channel on a daily basis.

As of now, his total net worth is believed to be in the range of $100,000, considering multiple sources of income such as advertisements, brand endorsements amongst others.

fields.title: Mizkif
fields.overview: Matthew Rinaudo is well-known as Mizkif who grew up in very downtrodden conditions. He suffers from viral myocarditis, which is a heart condition and has also needed medication for his ADHD from a considerable period of time.
fields.body:
Mizkif Career

Mizkif gained a lot of traction during the Presidential elections in the United States of America (USA) in 2020. During that period, he had become the third-most watched streamer on Twitch, as he regularly voiced his opinions on the developments.

His presence on the online medium began increasing upon his meeting with Iceposidon as Mizkif became the MMORPG streamer’s cameraman

He is perhaps one of the earliest streamers from the industry, having kicked off his career on this front way back in 2010.

However, his persona only started expanding from 2018 onwards though 2020 turned out to be Mizkif’s most successful year in his streaming career.

Close to 100,000 people watched him during his biggest stream ever as Mizkif unfurled his collection of very rare and unique Pokemon cards in that video.

He also made several sleep streams and raised close to $5600 from one such stream as well.

Teaming up with many other streamers, Mizkif also played the ‘Among Us’ game in 2020, which was a game that had gained a lot of popularity following the onset of the Covid-19 pandemic about a couple of years ago.

Mizkif engages in both Twitch and YouTube streams simultaneously, maintaining his popularity across both platforms. While his prominence on Twitch is very renowned, his total YouTube views have also reached close to the million mark.

Overall, Mizkif earns around $40,000-$50,000 per month from Twitch alone. His complete net worth stands at around $700,000 currently whereas his graded Nintendo gaming products alone command a net worth of close to $45,000. Both his channel and the widespread collection of rare gaming products have contributed to his massive net worth.

fields.title: Symfuhny
fields.overview: Mason Lanier, known as Symfuhny, is an American streamer best known for his Fortnite streams on Twitch. Mason first joined Twitch in 2018. Since then, he has amassed millions of followers on Twitch. Mason is also an official Twitch partner.
fields.body:
Symfuhny Carrer

Symfuhny Lanier is one of the youngest Fortnite and Twitch superstars who rose to popularity through his amazing editing skills and entertaining personality.

Symfuhny’s streaming career began with the game H1Z1, a battle royale game, which was fairly popular in the gaming community. However, with the rise of Fortnite Battle Royale on Twitch, H1Z1’s popularity teetered out. Symfuhny would switch his main game to Fortnite and this helped his channel grow.

His channel is still growing at a rapid pace and it is currently the 4th fastest growing Twitch channel according to Twitch Metrics. [2] Lanier was signed to NRG Esports in March of 2019 and has competed in several professional Fortnite events including the Fall and Summer Skirmishes.

Currently, Symfuhny is dating fellow Twitch streamer BrookeAB. Lanier’s immense popularity and supportive fanbase have helped both Symfuhny’s and BrookAB’s Twitch channels grow exponentially in 2019. Symfuhny has helped BrookeAB become the 5th fastest growing Twitch channel in June 2019 according to Twitch Metrics.

As of today, Symfuhny is an American YouTube channel that has a net worth of 196,000 dollars as of August 2020. Symfuhny is best known as a Twitch Star. Partner on Twitch who has garnered massive popularity as a Fortnite live-streaming gamer. He has seen his Twitch channel grow to boast more than 1.4 million followers. He was born on December 21, 1999, in the United States. He and TheMyth are both famous Twitch gamers known for their Fortnite streams. He published his first Twitch live stream in July 2018.

Symfuhny Awards and Achievements

At this time, Symfuhny is ranked #760 in highest overall earnings, and #151 in highest earnings for players from the United States.

Out of the 28 tournaments awarding cash prizes that Symfuhny had competed in, the largest amount was $20,250.00 from Fortnite Fall Skirmish Series – Week 6 – Stream-Invitational on October 28, 2018. He placed 11th, making up 11.29% of his total prize money won.

Symfuhny $100,000 Milestone

On October 28, 2018, Symfuhny arrived at the $100,000 milestone, winning $20,250.00 and placing 11th at Fortnite Fall Skirmish Series – Week 6 – Stream-Vitational. Prize money from 10 tournaments got him to that point.

Symfuhny Recent Earnings

Symfuhny has won $14,333.33 in prize money from 6 tournaments within the last 90 days, $1,000.00 (or 6.98%) of which came in the last month

fields.title: Cizzorz
fields.overview: John “Jack” Cizek better known online as Cizzorz, is an American YouTuber and Twitch streamer. Jack is well known for playing Fortnite with new players who have never gotten a “Victory Royale”. He has also gained a lot of recognition for creating death runs.
fields.body:
Cizzorz Carrer

John “Jack” Cizek better known online as Cizzorz, was born in Minnesota, and currently resides in Los Angeles. Jack is well known for playing Fortnite.

Jack started as a Black Ops YouTuber in 2011, he currently only has 2 public videos about them. Jack then has done Modern Warfare 3 montages and has also successfully attempted top records in Black Ops 3.

On March 13, 2018, Jack joined FaZe Clan because of his well-known Fortnite gameplays.

Cizzorz Bio

Cizzorz is a gaming YouTuber whose real name is Jack. He has an estimated net worth of $1.2 million

John “Jack” Cizek better known online as Cizzorz, is an American YouTuber and Twitch streamer who was born in Minnesota, and currently resides in Los Angeles. Jack is well known for playing Fortnite with new players who have never gotten a “Victory Royale”. Jack has also gained a lot of recognition for creating death runs. He is 24 years old and was born on April 25, 1996.

Cizzorz Awards and Achievements

Fortnite World Cup Creative Finals: FaZe Cizzorz wins at his own game

The first event of the Fortnite World Cup, the Creative Finals, took place on July 26. To compete, online trials tested players in various creative games. Those that stood out were picked by assorted Fortnite personalities called “Team Captains.” Some of the personalities included Tyler “Ninja” Blevins, Lachlan “Lachlan” Power, and Corentin “Gotaga” Houssein. In total, 32 players competed with four players on each team including the team captain. The Creative Finals challenged the teams on three separate player-made maps. All three maps were played three times. Then the Creative Finals reintroduced each map with a modification for the final round. Ultimately, team Fish Fam, headlined by Jack “Cizzorz”, took home the grand prize. Zand clutched the last life on the final map to secure the win.

Cizzorz Sky Station Showdown

The first map of the Creative Finals was the Sky Station Showdown. The game mode focused on maintaining control of certain checkpoints. The area was slightly smaller than two tiles by two tiles. To earn points, a team must keep enemy players from entering the zone. The team must also stay within the zone. After the three matches, the team “Funky Fighters” won the challenge and earned themselves $100,000.

Cizzorz Junkyard Juke

This game mode played like “Prop Hunt.” The major difference came from a central guard post in the middle where defending teams had to prevent players from reaching. The players outside of the guard post were disguised as various Fortnite items. They needed to avoid the guards’ sight while making their way toward the middle of the map. The teams rotated from the guards to props each round. Team “Chicken Champions” snuck out a win for a total of $110,000 in winnings.

Cizzorz World Run

This Creative map played like the famous Death Run by Cizzorz. It included different jumps, runs, and technical abilities to navigate. Players avoided traps, used impulse grenades to jump, and moved precisely around obstacles. The time a team finished and the number of coins collected determined which team won. Unsurprisingly, the team with the creator of the Death Run, “Fish Fam,” won this challenge and their share of prize money.

Cizzorz Golden Games

This mode took the three previous modes and introduced or removed a certain variable. For example, players respawned in the World Run mode at the last checkpoint. In the Golden Games, players received only one life to complete the challenge.

Team Fish Fam and FaZe Cizzorz win the Fortnite World Cup Creative Finals

The Creative Finals came down to the very last moment. Zand, a player on Fish Fam, remained the only player alive on the revamped World Run. He needed one more coin to beat the other teams. After a long pause, Zand nailed the jump and collected the coin. Then the celebration began! Cizzorz, Suezhoo, and HiImTylerH surrounded him with excitement as they all just won $325,000 from Fortnite.

Cizzorz History

Jack started as a Black Ops YouTuber in 2011, he currently only has 2 public videos about them. Jack then has done Modern Warfare 3 montages and has also successfully attempted top records in Black Ops 3. He got top 15 for being the fastest sidewinder freerun in Black Ops 3, Top 50 in Infected, and made a record of the fastest run in BlackOut Freerun. He has also done multiple challenges in Black Ops 3. His channel went up to 400,000 subscribers before making Fortnite content which puts him in the position he is in now. On March 13, 2018, Jack joined FaZe Clan because of his well-known Fortnite gameplays.

Cizzorz Death Run Challenges

Death Run 1.0

Ever since the release of Fortnite’s creative mode, Jack created a near-impossible obstacle course for everyone to play. Almost every big Fortnite streamer has attempted the obstacle course with barely anyone winning the game. According to the community, almost all of the levels are hard and long-term to beat. There are 10 levels. Jack has been credited and gained a lot of exposure for making the obstacle course and being the most played island in Fortnite Creative.

Winner

The Winner of the Death Run was Suezhoo, with a time of 3 minutes and 17 seconds. Jack commented on the video where the Death Run course record was held and gave Suezhoo $1,500.

Death Run 2.0

Since the results of the first map came to an end, Jack created another death run but will feature extra levels up to 13 approximately. It was released on January 9, 2018.

Levels Ruined

Sometime around January 5, a user had edit privileges and destroyed levels 11 – 13. This made the Death Run public release was forced to be delayed. Jack has mentioned that he is the only one to have edit permissions, but random players who entered Jack's course early had permissions and were able to vandalize the Death Run. Hours after the levels were vandalized, Jack checked replay mode and the user who was found to destroy the levels was iComethazine.

Winners

  • The winner of the course was hotball1, with a time of 6 minutes and 12 seconds, and received $3,500.
  • The second-place winner was eskay with a time of 6 minutes and 18 seconds and receive $1,000.
  • The third-place winner was PoopyFartyPee with a time of 6 minutes and 36 seconds. The fourth-place winner was Crump with a time of 7 minutes and 2 seconds.
  • The fifth winner was Suezhoo, the death run 1.0 winner, with a time of 7 minutes and 29 seconds.

    John “Jack” Cizek better known online as Cizzorz, was born in Minnesota, and currently resides in Los Angeles. Jack is well known for playing Fortnite.

    Death Run 3.0

    Jack has given a preview of his Death Run 3.0 on February 11, 2019. The course was in early release to Content Creators and Streamers on February 15, 2019. There are 16 levels in it, and the first few levels are simple for the amateurs but as tough as you progress.

    The top 10 content creators get paid. Place 1 gets $8,000. Place 2 gets $4,000. Place 3 gets $2,500. And place 4 through 10 gets $1,500.

    Winners

    • The winners were announced on February 20, 2019.
    • The winner of the course was Bizzle; receiving $8,000.
    • The second-place winner of the course was Liquid Chap; receiving $4,000.
    • The third place in the course was Vivid; receiving $2,500.
    • The fourth-place winner of the course was Lil mikeqt; receiving $1,500.
    • The fifth-place winner of the course was Saint; receiving $1,500.
    • The sixth-place winner of the course was Svennoss; receiving $1,500.
    • The seventh-place winner of the course was Tinny; receiving $1,500.
    • The eighth-place winner of the course was Mrfreshasian; receiving $1,500.
    • The ninth-place winner of the course was Typical Gamer; receiving $1,500.
    • The tenth place winner of the course was TSM Commandment; receiving $1,500.

      Public Release

      Since the winners for early release were announced, the death run was officially released to the public. The competition is still underway and the total price given away is $25,000.

      Winner

      For the public release, there was only 1 winner, and it was Hotball1 with a time of 5 minutes and 24 seconds; winning $10,000.

      Cizzorz Controversy

      Death Run Challenge Map 2 Code Leaked

      On January 6, 2019, a user named DectOfficial leaked the code of Jack’s unreleased Death Run. Jack went on to Dect’s stream and was asked Dect to take down the code. Dect did do so but then went against Jack for his behavior towards Dect. Jack did cuss at Dect (not in a way to harass or bully) because of the fury Jack was in. Dect went on a rant and claims Jack is being disrespectful and encouraged his fans to send hate toward Dect, which is not the case. Dect claims that he thought the code was public, which was why he shared the code and live-streamed himself playing the unreleased Death Run.

      Jack did apologize for his behavior and Dect also apologized for leaking the code and for his behavior as well. Jack did also mention the hate people are giving towards other streamers, and hoping that he will never see those people again.

      Milestones

      Subscriber Milestones

      1 million subscribers March 1, 2018
      2 million subscribers June 6, 2018
      3 million subscribers November 28, 2018
      4 million subscribers March 3, 2019

      Views Milestones

      100 million views February 18, 2018
      200 million views May 19, 2018
      300 million views September 10, 2018
      400 million views January 21, 2019

fields.title: DrDisRespect
fields.overview: Herschel Guy Beahm IV better known online as DrDisRespect is an American YouTuber, streamer, and gamer, who has gained success for his appearance on live streams. He is a professional H1Z1 and PUBG player and has competed in many tournaments. Herschel was one of the most popular Twitch Streamers on the platform, but had since been banned and made a switch to YouTube.
fields.body:
DrDisRespect Carrer

DrDisRespect is a professional H1Z1 and PUBG player and has competed in tournaments against other good players.

On March 16, 2011, Beahm was appointed as the community manager of Sledgehammer Games. He was promoted to level designer and helped create many of the multiplayer maps for Call of Duty: Advanced Warfare.

According to Beahm, on September 11, 2018, an unknown person shot at his house with a BB gun and hit an upstairs window. This was reportedly the second time that someone shot at his house. On January 10, 2019, Creative Artists Agency signed Beahm as a client.

Herschel Guy Beahm IV better known online as DrDisRespect (referred to as the Doc), is an American YouTuber, streamer, and gamer, who has gained success for his appearance on live streams. He is a professional H1Z1 and PUBG player and has competed in tournaments against other good players. Herschel still plays Blackout, Apex Legends, H1Z1, and Fortnite on YouTube Live alongside a variety of shooter games. Herschel was one of the most popular Twitch Streamers on the platform, but had since been banned and made a switch to YouTube and live-streamed from there. He is 38 years old and was born on March 10, 1982.

Dr. DisRespect Career and Personal life

Beahm graduated from California State Polytechnic University, Pomona in 2005, where he played NCAA Division II basketball.

Beahm’s first video was posted on January 11, 2010, showing the gameplay of Call of Duty: Modern Warfare 2. He was featured in multiple videos for the gaming channel Machinima, mostly playing Call of Duty. Beahm went inactive from YouTube in late 2011 and did not release any content for nearly five years.

On March 16, 2011, Beahm was appointed as the community manager of Sledgehammer Games. He was promoted to level designer and helped create many of the multiplayer maps for Call of Duty: Advanced Warfare. Beahm joined Justin. tv (now Twitch) while he was working at Sledgehammer. He quit Sledgehammer in 2015 to focus on a full-time streaming career

Beahm gained a following from playing battle royale games, starting with H1Z1 before switching to PlayerUnknown’s Battlegrounds and then moving on to Call of Duty: Black Ops 4. In December 2017, he took a two-month hiatus from streaming to tend to his relationship with his wife, after having admitted to being unfaithful to her. Beahm and his wife have a daughter. He returned on February 5, 2018, with a total peak of 388,000 concurrent viewers, just shy of beating Tyler1’s record of 410,000. His popularity has led to sponsorship deals with Gillette, ASUS, Razer, and G Fuel.

According to Beahm, on September 11, 2018, an unknown person shot at his house with a BB gun and hit an upstairs window. This was reportedly the second time that someone shot at his house. On January 10, 2019, Creative Artists Agency signed Beahm as a client.

Dr. DisRespect Streaming persona

Beahm is regarded as an entertainer in the streaming industry, rather than a “professional gamer.” ESPN describes him as “a WWE character in the competitive gaming world”, and he has himself said “I created a character who plays multiplayer video games, and he’s considered the most dominating gaming specimen.

When playing as the Dr. Disrespect character, Beahm wears a black mullet wig, sunglasses, a red or black long-sleeved athletic moisture-wicking shirt, and a red or black tactical vest. One of his most notable catchphrases is “I’m on top of the mountain, and I’m only halfway up!”, and his motto is “Violence. Speed. Momentum”. He sports a mustache he has named “Slick Daddy” aka “The Poisonous Ethiopian Caterpillar”

Dr. DisRespect Controversies

E3 bathroom filming incident

On June 11, 2019, Beahm’s DrDisrespect Twitch channel was suspended as he was IRL streaming (“in real life”) while attending the 2019 edition of the Electronic Entertainment Expo (E3) in Los Angeles, California. Beahm’s cameraman followed him into a public restroom (he re-entered the bathroom on two occasions, with filming still going on) at the venue in violation of Twitch’s privacy rules and privacy laws in the California Penal Code. In addition, E3 organizer Entertainment Software Association revoked Beahm’s E3 pass, banning him from the event. Twitch reinstated the DrDisrespect channel on June 25

Racism accusation

Musician Jimmy Wong compiled a series of clips in which Beahm caricatures Chinese accents and language and accused him of racism on this basis. In response, Beahm claimed that some of his best friends are Asian and called the criticism “laughable”.

A permanent ban from Twitch

On June 26, 2020, the DrDisrespect Twitch account was banned from Twitch. Twitch’s official statement on the ban said “As is our process, we take appropriate action when we have evidence that a streamer has acted in violation of our Community Guidelines or Terms of Service. These apply to all streamers regardless of status or prominence in the community”. No specific details have been released. On June 27, Beahm tweeted that he had not yet been informed of the exact reason for the ban. On July 16, 20 days after he was banned, he broke his silence and was interviewed by PC Gamer and the Washington Post; insisting that he still does not know why Twitch banned him from the platform, that his contracts were still in good standing, debunks any “crazy speculation” or theory that developed and is focusing on his upcoming “Doc 3.0” personality. He was reportedly struggling to search “for words and issued several stuttering responses to questions” about it during one of the interviews.

On August 6, after 42 days of not streaming, he tweeted a link to his YouTube channel with the caption “Tomorrow, we arrive.”He went live on YouTube at the same time, but the stream only showed a looping video of a custom Champions Club gas station. He also confirmed that he would show up on stream at midnight PT on the following day. On August 7th, DrDisrespect returned to his stream at 1 PM PST. The reason for his ban remains unknown.

fields.title: GeorgeNotFound
fields.meta_description: George Henry Davidson also known as GeorgeNotFound is a popular British Minecraft gamer and YouTube content creator.
fields.overview: George Henry Davidson also known as GeorgeNotFound is a popular British Minecraft gamer and YouTube content creator.
fields.body:
GeorgeNotFound Career

George Henry Davidson was born on November 1, 1996. He has graduated with a degree in computer science.

On April 15, 2020, George confirmed via Twitter that he has severe protanopia (red-green color blindness). He bought colorblind glasses to help him distinguish between red-green colors. On September 9, 2020, he uploaded his reaction to him being able to differentiate color properly for the first time. He doesn’t own a driving license and so he cannot drive.

George grew up with his sister. He is pretty fond of animals and has a long history with pets. He has nicknamed his cat Pooper for defecating on his bed whom he got in Late October 2019. The real name of the cat is Luca. On July 28, 2020, George revealed during a livestream (and later on Twitter) that he had noticed Luca was breathing strangely and so took him to the vet. Luca was then diagnosed with a rare and incurable disease and had to be put down.

He now has a dog that he got in August of 2020 whose name is not yet released.

On October 17, 2020, Dream posted a picture of George new kitten, taken a few days previous to the tweet. Their name has not been released as well. George often posts pictures with them, and they have been featured in his Twitch livestreams.

George is a big fan of Harry Potter. His favorite music artist is Travis Scott. George played CS:GO and was a global ranker.

Minecraft Championships

George participated in the MC Championships 6, as part of Team Lime Llamas, with Dream, TheEret, and Mefs. He was placed 12th individually, while his team ranked third overall.

In MC Championships 7, he played as part of Team Purple Pandas, with Dream, Sylvee, and Sapnap. He was placed 22nd individually, and the team ranked fourth overall George participated in MC Championships 8, as part of Team Green Guardians, teaming up with Sapnap, TheEret, and Krtzyy. He sells his own merchandise, such as hoodies and T-shirts, on georgenotfound.shop.

Dream SMP

George is a member of the Dream Team, having the second most subscribers out of the three. He has been uploading current YouTube videos publicly since 2019, but has been on the platform since 2013. George is the co-founder of the Dream SMP with Dream.

Meeting Dream

George and Dream met on MunchyMC, BadBoyHalo Minecraft server. Dream was an admin and developer, and George was a coder. Their first interaction was when Dream asked George for help on coding a plugin, but after getting ignored, Dream decided to learn how to code it himself, which kickstarted him becoming an even better coder.

Meeting Sapnap

During a stream on June 22, 2020, when asked how he met Sapnap, he said that he may have met him through a Minecraft server. However, he walked back on the statement to say that Dream most likely introduced the two, but he was not entirely sure.

fields.title: TommyInnit
fields.overview: TommyInnit is a Twitch personality who streams games like PUBG, Fortnite, Bed Wars amongst others on the platform.
fields.body:
Tommylnnit Career

He started posting Hypixel Skyblock from August 2019 onwards and instantly garnered about 200,000 subscribers on his channel.

His subscriber base on YouTube shot up by over 150 percent within a month to 66,000 subscribers in late 2019 and this opened up several newer avenues for him, such as an invite from the private SMP SMPEarth.

Like many other popular streamers, Tommy became the center of all attraction by playing Minecraft online with fellow contemporaries such as Slimecicle, Ph1lza Minecraft, Tubbo, and Wilbur Soot amongst others.

It can be said that Tommy has a comprehensive understanding of expanding his footprint in this space. That is why, in his initial heydays, the gamer put out videos in which he hacked on the Minecraft VR.

He had also put out in open certain unrevealed details regarding The Archon server during that time.

TommyInnit usually makes videos where he plays Minecraft with mods, enjoying the game and its new modifications with his friends, most notably Wilbur Soot, Quackity, Slimecicle, Tubbo, and Ph1lza Minecraft.
