NaDeSHoT had his first top 8 placement at MLG National Championship 2009 during Call of Duty 4: Modern Warfare season with the same team, finishing 4th. After Call of Duty 4: Modern Warfare, NaDeSHoT went to OpTic Gaming for the Call of Duty: Modern Warfare 2 season. Here, Nade would find two 8th place finishes at MLG Online National Championship and MLG National Championship 2010.

Black Ops and Modern Warfare 3

Matt would stay on the Optic Gaming squad heading into the Call of Duty: Black Ops season. Here, he would find a 3rd place finish at MLG Dallas 2011 before being moved to OpTic Nation. After a 6th place finish at MLG Columbus 2011, Nadeshot would be released from OpTic, and would find himself on Team EnVyUs. He would find two more Top 8 finishes while on EnVy as the Black Ops season came to a close. During the Call of Duty: Modern Warfare 3 season, Matt would find himself back on Optic Gaming. Nadeshot and the squad of MerK, BigTymeR, and Vengeance would win Call of Duty XP, but after a 3rd place finish at UMG Classic, he was once again released from OpTic Gaming. At the UMG Invitational, he would find himself on JuKeD, where he would place 4th. Finally, he would place 3rd at the UMG Championships with a pick up team to finish the season.

Black Ops 2

NaDeSHoT would find himself back on OpTic once again for the Call of Duty: Black Ops 2 season. Here, along with Scump, MerK, and BigTymeR, they would find their highest placing early in the season, finishing 1st at UMG Chicago. The team would go on to place 3rd at the Call of Duty Championship, and would not place out of the top 10 for the rest of the season. However, many would begin to question why the team had dropped Rambo in favor of NaDeSHoT. Eventually, OpTic would replace MerK with JKap, and this line up would finish with a 2nd place finish at the MLG Fall Invitational 2013

Ghosts

Nadeshot and company would have a rough start to the Call of Duty: Ghosts season, finishing outside of the top 10 at the first 2 events they would attend. The team would go through a flurry of roster changes at one point, including Ricky, Saints, and Parasite, and the retirement of BigTymeR. Scump would leave the team for a week to join Team EnVyUs, siting a rivalry with Nadeshot as the reason. However, Scump would return, and the team would be complete with Nadeshot, Scump, MBoZe, and Clayster. Many doubted the team heading into the Call of Duty Championship 2014, especially after barely qualifying at the U.S. Regional tournament, but the team would make a strong run, finishing 3rd overall for the 2nd year in a row. After Champs, OpTic would make a surprise move by reviving OpTic Nation, with MBoZe as the captain. OpTic would bring on ProoFy to fill his spot, and the squad would head into UGC Niagara 2014 with high expectations. However, the squad would finish in 7th place, with many questioning why they made the change at all. Optic Gaming would then attend the MLG X Games Invitational 2014, where NaDeSHoT would show his Search and Destroy prowess, helping lead OpTic Gaming to a win over Team Kaliber in the Grand Finals, and becoming the first Call of Duty X Games gold medalists. Following this win, NaDeSHoT and the rest of the OpTic Gaming squad went into MLG Anaheim 2014 full of confidence and looked to turn their 2nd seed from Season 2 of the MLG CoD league into a victory. They would take out all opposition 3-0 until they faced Evil Geniuses who knocked them down into the losers bracket final. They went onto beat TCM-Gaming 3-0 in this series and faced Evil Geniuses again in the Championship final. However, the lost the continuation series and finished with a very convincing 2nd. OpTic Gaming would then look to carry this form over to London at Gfinity 3 but they were unable to, finishing with a disappointing 5th-8th with no-one really performing. Following this disappointment they looked to bounce back at UMG Dallas 2014, but only did so in part, finishing 4th and taking away $2,000 after crashing out at the hands of OpTic Nation who beat them with a convincing 3-0. NaDeSHoT and his teammates at OpTic Gaming finished 3rd in the Season 3 of the MLG CoD league, and secured the 3rd seed going into the Season 3 Playoff. In the Season 3 of the MLG league playoff they lost in the first round against Denial eSports, after beating both Rise Nation and OpTic Nation with a convincing 3-0, NaDeSHoT and his team lost 3-0 to Most Wanted, OpTic Gaming finished in 4th place to close out the Call of Duty: Ghosts season..

Advanced Warfare

Nadeshot and company began the Advanced Warfare season well at MLG Columbus Open 2014 as they placed second, losing out to FaZe Clan in the Grand Final after OpTic Gaming released Clayster and ProoFy for FormaL and Crimsix. OpTic Gaming went on to win three consecutive tournaments: UMG Orlando 2015, MLG Pro League Season 1 Playoffs, and the Call of Duty Championship 2015: NA Regional Finals. However, at the Call of Duty Championship 2015, OpTic Gaming got a disappointing 7th place finish, shocking everyone involved. On 04/04/2015, feeling that he was the reason for his team’s poor performance at CoD Champs 2015, Nadeshot announced that he would be “taking a break” from competitive Call of Duty, and would be focusing more on his YouTube channel and live streaming. This shocked all the competitive Call of Duty community, as well as most of the pros. It was later announced that Karma would replace him on OpTic Gaming.

Post Retirement

On April 18, 2016, NaDeSHoT announced on his YouTube channel that he created his own organization known as “Hundred Thieves.” He had acquired a team that had recently qualified for Stage 2 of the 2016 COD World League North America Pro Division that went by the name of, “King Papey,” to be the first team in any eSports to represent his organization. He also announced that this organisation will not be limited to Call of Duty eSports and is interested in the idea of picking up teams in games like Counter Strike: Global Offensive, Dota, and others.

fields.title: Stable Ronaldo
fields.overview: Stable Ronaldo is a professional Fortnite player, and also a relevant streamer on the platform Twitch. Ronaldo was born on 14 January 2003 in America. He goes by the online moniker 'Stable Ronaldo' on all his socials. Ronaldo started his online career as a Fortnite streamer, soon his content gained popularity on the platform and he gathered many viewers. He is most known for his Fortnite gameplay and entertaining videos on his Youtube channel.
fields.body:
Stable Ronaldo Carrer

Ronaldo became a big name in the community after winning the FNCS trios in 2019. He was signed by BuiltByGamers and started competing with their roster. Ronaldo has since joined NRG Esports and switched his focus more to streaming and making content. Currently, his Youtube channel boasts over a million subscribers and his Twitch has over 2.3 million followers. Stable Ronaldo is also delving into variety streaming trying out different games and sometimes just interacting with his audience. He is seen hosting watch parties with other popular streamers like Clix and reacting to TikToks.

Ronaldo has been a controversial figure in the gaming community, often due to his outspoken and upfront personality. He has been banned by Epic Games on multiple occasions some of which include inappropriate gamer-tags and other acts of notoriety. The young Fortnite prodigy has also faced bans on Twitch due to various suspected reasons. His most recent ban came in December of 2021 when his account was imposed with a 24 hour ban. Twitch never disclosed the specific reason for this ban however it was most likely caused due to inexplicit content shown by Ronaldo on his stream. 

The VOD which was later featured on Youtube shows Ronaldo playing a clip sent to him by his fellow friend and streamer Clix. The clip featured sexually inexplicit content which was hastily closed by Ronaldo. Before his Twitch ban Ronaldo also made stirs on the internet claiming to sue Epic Games for stalking his account activity. He also made bold claims that Epic monitored his account with regulations much more strict than for normal users.

fields.title: NiKo
fields.overview: Nikola Kovač alias NiKo (formerly known as NiKolinho and nIKOLINHO) is Counter-Strike: Global Offensive professional player for G2 Esports. NiKo has been considered as one of the best CS:GO rifler on the planet. He has also played Counter-Strike as a semi-pro in the beginning of his pro career.
fields.body:
Niko Carrer

Nikola Kovač (alias NiKo) is a CS:GO professional for G2 Esports. He is 25 years old and was born on Feb. 16, 1997, in a city called Brčko in northern Bosnia and Herzegovina.

NiKo first played Counter-Strike as 9-years-old when his parents introduced him to an internet café. From the beginning, Counter-Strike for NiKo was about being better than everyone around him.

From 2010 to 2012, NiKo played Counter-Strike 1.6 (or Half-Life: Counter-Strike) as a semi-professional player for several teams. But his pro scene begins with foolproof. Other teams he played were eu4ia, neWave, maksnet, DEFUSE.maksnet, iNation, and myDGB.

iNation was his last team for whom he played as a Counter-Strike professional. Later in the same year, 2012, when the Counter-Strike: Global Offensive was released, he quickly transitioned with the same team.

That's where NiKo's actual journey as a CS:GO professional begins in 2012.

NiKo's Career as a Counter-Strike 1.6 professional

Unknown – 2011 FullProof
2011-05-04 – 2011-(Unknow date) eu4ia
2011-12-03 – 2011-12-06 neWave
2011-12-17 - Unknown maksnet
Unknown - 2012 DEFUSE.maksnet
2012 - 2012 iNation
2012 - 2012 myDGB
2012 - Unknown iNation

NiKo Career as CS:GO professional

From 2012 to 2015, NiKo first started playing with iNation as a CS:GO profession but also played for several other teams; e-Sports.rs, Team Refuse, and GamePub while taking breaks from iNation.

NiKo primarily played with Serbian rosters and was dedicated to elevating his region to reach new heights in the Counter-Strike pro scene. He mentioned during an interview that he wanted to become great with a regional roster so badly he even declined an offer to join MOUZ (formerly known as mouseports).

When I was turning 18 I got my first offer from Mousesports which I declined. I still believe I can make it to the top with a Serbian team. I did not tell it to my parents because I know they would force me to to accept the offer. Because they knew that I wanted this since I was a kid.

However, after 2 years of playing with regional CS:GO, teams. NiKo accepted the second offer from MOUZ on the 4th of March, 2015. 

NiKo played so well in the pro scene. His team was often dubbed "Nikosports" due to his amazing individual performances, one of them being his Deagle ace in the cache against FaZe Clan in 2015.

The whole of 2016, he played for MOUZ, and during this same time they won Acer Predator Masters Season 2 and ranked 3-4th in ELEAGUE Season 1, ESL One: New York 2016 European Qualifier, ESL Pro League Season 4 - Europe, and ESL Pro League Season 4 - Finals.

NiKo with FaZe Clan

On the 9th of February 2017, NiKo left MOUZ and was acquired by FaZe Clan to garner together a star-player team. Kovač's first big tournament win was at StarLadder i-League StarSeries Season 3, followed by a winless period of five months with a near-miss at Esports Championship Series Season 3. 

Following a re-shuffle of the FaZe roster, bringing in the 2015's two best players, Olof olofmeister Kajbjer Gustafsson and Ladislav GuardiaN Kovács, FaZe was rejuvenated and managed back-to-back flawless victories at ESL One: New York 2017 and ELEAGUE CS:GO Premier 2017. Following this, the team went two months without a win before taking the Esports Championship Series Season 4 trophy over MOUZE at the end of the year. He was ranked #2 in the year-end HLTV top 20 and had a competition with coldzera throughout the year.

During his time with FaZe Clan, he was ranked 2nd, 3rd, and 11th in HLTV's best player rankings in respective years 2017, 2018, and 2019. He was also awarded as an MVP in many tournaments by HLTV.

In 2020, the last year of NiKo with FaZe Clan, he with his team marked another victory at IEM New York EU and won $70,000.

NiKo with G2 Esports

After a staggering, three and a half year journey, NiKo was acquired by G2 Esports, where his cousin huNter was also a part of the team. Till this time, Kovač has won pretty much everything else there is to win in the world of CS:GO, including ELEAGUE, ESL One, and multiple BLAST events apart from a Major. 

Esports earnings calculate his winnings at $750,925.13, making him the 24th highest earner in CS:GO history and one of the best players on that list who has never have won a major.

NiKo was back in his old form again, and he was ranked 4th in the HLTV's best player ranking of the year 2020.

He led his team to the grand finals of the 2021 PGL Major but wasn't able to defeat a dominant Na'Vi team. They also were runner-up to the same Na'Vi team at Intel Extreme Masters XVI - Cologne earlier in the year. He went through a career-best run in the 2nd half of 2021 with CSGO's return to LAN. He finished third in the HLTV top 20, behind ZywOo and S1mple.

NiKo's Records

  1. NiKo Holds the record for kills in a map at a Major after scoring 52 against FlipSid3 Tactics at MLG Columbus 2016.
  2. He is the first player to win multiple HLTV MVP awards in three consecutive years. 
  3. Previously held the record for kills in regulation at a big event or any match between top teams on LAN with 40 against Team Liquid at ECS Season 4 Finals. NiKo's record was later taken over by KRIMZ who dropped 44 against MIBR at ESL Pro League Season 10: Finals.
  4. He is the 7th player (the previous 6 being Zeus, GuardiaN, olofmeister, s1mple, allu, and AdreN) to make a Major final with two different teams, with FaZe Clan at ELEAGUE Major: Boston 2018 and G2 Esports at PGL Major Stockholm 2021.

fields.title: Magnum
fields.overview: Magnum is a professional Valorant player who is of Czech nationality. He currently plays for the Valorant Team Fnatic. His real name is Martin Penkov and he is of 20 years of age currently.
fields.body:
Magnum Carrer

Martin was born on August 9, 2001. His main agents are Killjoy and Viper. Magnum has previously showcased his skill playing for other major teams in the CIS region. This includes teams like Avenue Esports and Enterprise Esports. His most recent stint was at Team Homeless which was a European team following which he joined the Fnatic roster.

Martin joined Fnatic in April of 2021 and plays alongside Boaster, Derke and Braveaf. Fnatic signed Magnum alongside Derke to replace two of its benched players. The duo replaced Muhammad “Moe40” Hariff and Kostas “tsack” Theodoropoulos from the main roster. Both Magnum and Boaster made their debut for Fnatic in the Challengers Two Open qualifiers. 

The team had previously failed to qualify for the Masters with its previous squad and thus felt the need for change. Since the arrival of fresh talent in the form of Martin and Derke, Fnatic has risen to the top of CIS region. They were the finalists at the VCT 2021 Reykjavik Masters, finishing only second to Sentinels. This second place finish granted them $50,000. Magnum and his total tournament earnings are expected to be around $40,000.

fields.title: BraveAF
fields.overview: BraveAF is a professional Valorant player who is of Russian nationality. He currently plays for the Valorant Team Fnatic. His real name is Andrey Gorchakov and he is currently 26 years of age. Fnatic signed him a month before VCT Challengers to strengthen their squad. Andrey is a young and promising player with lots of potential.
fields.body:
BraveAF Carrer

According to Fnatic coaches, he is extremely motivated and has an enormous skill ceiling. BraveAF is known for its thought-out plays and intelligent utility usage. He was previously a part of Teams such as Team Finest and One Breath Gaming. During his time in these teams he cemented himself as a great player in the CIS region. He currently stars alongside a star studded roster with Boaster, Mistic, Derke, Magnum & Coach Mini. 

Considering his brilliant utility play his main agent is Sova. He also plays Skye and sometimes plays Sage. Andrey fills the initiator role for his team. He was signed by Fnatic in January of 2022 and has currently featured only once for the black and orange. His first showing for Fnatic ended in a victory against G2 Esports. BraveAF shined with agents such as Sova and Sage gathering 20 assists and an ACS of 201.

fields.title: D3ffo
fields.overview: Nikita “d3ffo” Sudakov is a Russian player who is currently playing for Gambit Esports.
fields.body:
D3ffo Career

D3ffo joined Gambit Esports from Sharp-Clan on 28th September 2020. He has an aggressive playstyle and usually haunts the server with his signature agent, Jett. D3ffo is an aggressive awper, known for early-round pickoffs. He usually fills the duelist role for his team. He also plays Skye for his team apart from his usual Jett.

Nikita “d3ffo” Sudakov is a Russian player who is currently playing for Gambit Esports.

D3ffo joined Gambit Esports from Sharp-Clan on 28th September 2020. He has an aggressive playstyle and usually haunts the server with his signature agent, Jett. D3ffo is an aggressive awper, known for early-round pickoffs. He usually fills the duelist role for his team. He also plays Skye for his team apart from his usual Jett.

D3ffo has been a crucial cog in the system for Gambit. His Jett has performed on the big stage and had an average ACS of 200+ for the Champions Tour CIS Stage 3: Challengers 1, which Gambit went on to win. Gambit also 3-0’d Envy in the Valorant Champions Tour Stage 3: Masters Berlin and d3ffo played a huge role. He played Jett on all three maps and provided a total of 13 entry frags. He had the most amount of entries on Bind adding up at 7. Gambit went on to win $225,000 winning against Envy.

fields.title: EpikWhale
fields.overview: EpikWhale is a popular Fortnite streamer whose real name is Shane Cotton. He is also a content creator, who posts his gameplay videos on Youtube and has thousands of followers.
fields.body:
EpikWhale Career

Shaun is from America and has American citizenship. He was born on August 3rd, 2002. Epikwhale is currently signed to the gaming organization NRG and is amongst some of its youngest members being just 20. He started playing games at an early age which mainly consisted of MMOs directed toward children. His favorite game was Disney’s Club Penguin. He was introduced to Fortnite by his brother when it was released in 2017. Soon he was addicted to the game and played almost regularly honing his skills.

He played Fortnite every night until 11 pm, right after he had finished dinner and his homework from school. Shaun recalls having a standing proclivity towards Rubik’s cubes, this made him realize that he enjoyed strategic problem-solving. All of these traits alongside tons of practice and self-discipline have contributed to Epikwhale’s exceptional skill in Fortnite.

Shaun is still studying and does prioritize his studies. His schoolwork is extremely important to him, and he attends to his duties regularly. He has shared that his discipline and time management are also skills that he has worked on. He only streams or plays Fortnite after he is done finishing his school work.

Career and Net Worth

Shaun competed in numerous tournaments in 2019. He was successful in qualifying for the Fortnite World Cup finals. This raised the attention of many big organizations and he joined NRG Esports in July of 2019. He was their youngest member at the time being only 16. Epikwhale was later ranked 3rd in the Fortnite World Cup Finals which earned him USD 1.2 million.

He has decided to take a gap year after finishing high school to pursue his professional career in Fortnite alongside NRG Esports. His parents and family are very supportive of his goals and ambitions. This comes as no surprise given his talent and achievements in the e-sports scene thus far. His older brother still plays Fortnite with him and supports him.

Shaun is ranked #70 in overall earnings and #6 among the highest-earning players from America. He had earned around USD 1.3 million from tournaments and cash prizes even before he turned 18. It took him 34 tournaments and it accounts for more than 95% of his net worth even today. The biggest cash prize he has won was the $1,200,000.00 from Fortnite World Cup Finals Solo-2019. His 3rd place finish makes up for more than 80% of his net worth.

Shaun achieved success in a short span of just 8 tournaments, breaking the 100 grand mark on his prize earnings. He currently has 200k subscribers on Youtube and 356k followers on Twitch.

Teaming Up With Sealmatt

Teaming up with other players or helping them in Solo tournaments ruins the game for other players and is against the spirit of fair play. However, collaborating in Solo matches is more common than it should be in Open events which determine which players qualify for the high-level tournaments. Epic cannot keep an eye on every player and every play being made hence the integrity is to be maintained by the players.

People who intentionally break the rules gain an unfair advantage and ruin the entire point of these qualifying matches. Epikwhale and Sealmatt were caught exchanging healing items after the latter was heard asking for help. The shields Epikwhale gave Sealmatt bailed him out of an awkward fight and this made the game unfair for other competitors. This may be a minor altercation but this also indicates that both the players were in constant communication while the solo game lasted.

fields.title: Arteezy
fields.overview: Artour ‘Arteezy’ Babaev is a Canadian professional Dota II player. He is currently an Evil Geniuses team player. Arteezy also runs a very popular live stream channel, where he amasses a high count of viewers on account of his entertaining personality, excellent taste in music, and his brilliant gameplaying skills.
fields.body:
Arteezy Career

Arteezy also runs a very popular live stream channel, where he amasses a high count of viewers on account of his entertaining personality, excellent taste in music, and brilliant gameplaying skills.

Before playing Dota II, Arteezy was a Starcraft II and Dota I player. He had reached master by playing Protos before he had started with Dota II. The 16-year-old prodigy was then picked up by Kanishka ‘Sam’. ‘BuLba’ Sosale and Gustav ‘s4’ Magnusson for Dota II.

In January 2014, Arteezy created the team SAD BOYS along with other legendary players. This team was an instant hit, winning 16 out of their first 18 matches. This run included their undefeated championship victory at the Electronic Sports Prime/Shock Therapy Cup. SAD BOYS squad was acquired by Evil Geniuses on the 21st of February, 2014. This team won their first LAN tournament at the Monster Energy Invitational on the 7th of March, 2014 against Cloud9.

Arteezy then joined Team Secret, now playing in the capacity of the hard carry role. This team, including Zai, Team Secret was hailed immediately as the best team in the world. They routed through Dota II Asia Championships 15-0, with Arteezy exhibiting prodigious gameplay with his signature heroes Lycan and Shadow Fiend. But this team was defeated by Vici Gaming 2-1 in the upper-bracket semifinals. In the lower-bracket semifinals, Arteezy saw his team being defeated by his previous team Evil Geniuses 2-0. Arteezy however would get his revenge later, as Team Secret defeated Evil Geniuses 3-1 in the penultimate stages of both The Summit III and ESL One Frankfurt 2015.
However, due to a laggard phase of Team Secret, Arteezy rejoined Evil Geniuses as the hard carry player.

Achievements

Arteezy has won the IIIrd place at TI4 & TI8, but he is yet to win any Valve tournaments as of now. Fans have attributed a ‘third place curse’ on the Evil Geniuses as a meme as well. Although Arteezy has left his streaming behind, he used to be one of the most-watched Dota II streamers in the yesteryears. Even today, he attracts hordes of Dota II fans whenever he chooses to stream.

Arteezy, with his lane dominance and game impact, has revolutionized how midline is played in Dota II according to gaming experts. He has hovered around the topmost solo MMRs in Dota II leaderboards. He became only the second player in the history of Dota II to achieve the distinction of a matchmaking rating above 9000. Arteezy is also just the third player in the history of Dota II to achieve a matchmaking rating over 10000. He also reached an MMR of 11000 on the 18th of October, 2020, a day which is still celebrated by Dota II fans world-over.

fields.title: Moo
fields.overview: David ‘Moo’ Hull is a professional Dota II player from the United States of America, who is currently playing for the team IV Zoomers.
fields.body:
Moo Career

At the age of 14, Moo was inspired by the players' Destiny and Catz to become professional gamers. While initially being a Starcraft player, Moo lost interest in this game and turned to Dota II.

He started playing in Sunday Evening Cup Series, FaceIt, and NEL to eventually rise through the ranks in the North American Dota II scene, enough to get attention from pro teams. Moo joined his first professional team, Root Gaming, on the 8th of May, 2015. He then joined Team Fire, which was subsequently picked up by Team Archon.

After shameful results in the Shanghai Major, Moo left Archon and joined Digital Chaos. David Hull was able to compete at TI 2016 after defeating CG 3-2 in the finals of TI 2016 Americas Qualifiers. He played a pivotal role for Digital Chaos in the match against EG, when he played Beastmaster. In this match, despite being down by experience and gold, DC used a split-pushing tactic (while avoiding direct fights) and managed to get mega creeps while they left their Ancient exposed. This led to an eventual demolishment of EG’s Ancient. After this stint, he joined Complexity Gaming as their offlaner.

Achievements

David ‘Moo’ Hull was ranked one of the top offenders in the Dota II 2016 TI. In TI6, he was one of the top performers with an overall average of 3.70 KDA in the series. His role Beastmaster has a 90% win rate across the TI, and his signature ‘Timbersaw’ garnered 75 %, with an average KDA of 4.35.

fields.title: Chapix
fields.overview: Chapix is a professional Fortnite player who is currently representing Falcon Esports. He is of Swedish nationality and 17 years of age. Chapix was born on June 4, 2004, and his real name is Moussa Faour.
fields.body:
Chapix career

Chapix is part of a trio that includes two other players named Hen and Jannis. Together they have held dominance over the European region and have won multiple esports events. Chapix has been part of numerous organizations throughout his career as an esports athlete. He kicked off his venture with Valhall Vikings and later was a part of Team Overtime. Currently, he is part of the European organization Falcon Esports. 

The most amount of money he has gathered from a tournament is from FNCS Season 5 Grand Finals back in March of 2021. The 100 grand he won still constitutes a large amount of his net worth. He has also won Frosty Frenzy and a couple of Cash Cups with his trio.

fields.title: Wavy Jacob
fields.overview: Wavy Jacob is a Youtuber from the United States who is primarily known for Fortnite. He also makes videos on NBA 2k which is a game based on basketball.
fields.body:
Jacob Carrer

Jacob is an 18-year-old Youtuber from America. He was born on September 20, 2003. His videos mostly feature gameplay from Fortnite Battle Royale and NBA 2k20. He was born and raised in California, America. He is Caucasian by ethnicity and American by nationality. Jacob started playing video games at an early age as he was fascinated by platformers and console games. 

There is no information about his schooling although he is 18. It is safe to say Jacob is still in highschool. He posts almost every week on his Youtube channel. His first video was posted back in 2017, which featured his NBA gameplay. Currently his channel features over 300 videos with around half a million subscribers. It can be said from looking at his socialblade statistics that his tally of total views is around 15 million. 

He received a silver play button from Youtube for surpassing 100k subscribers in 2018. An estimate of Jacob's net worth is around $1 million dollars for the year 2021. Most of his revenue is generated from Youtube and brand endorsements.

fields.title: Nivera
fields.overview: Nabil “Nivera” Benrlitom is a Belgian player who currently plays for Team Liquid. He is a former Counter-Strike: Global Offensive player known for his time in Team Heretics and Team Vitality. He is Adil “ScreaM” Benrlitom’s younger brother.
fields.body:
Nivera Career

Nivera is the newest addition to the Team Liquid roster, having joined from Team Vitality. He made the switch from Counter-Strike to join his brother Scream and lead Team Liquid to success in a new game and a fresh competitive scene.

Nivera joined Team Liquid on 25th September 2021 from Team Vitality. He usually plays Viper and Killjoy, holding sites and providing utility for his team. He has also recently developed setups for Cypher and is trying to learn to adapt to newer agents.

Nivera being the newest member is yet to face many challenges with his new team. His most recent final was the Champions Tour EMEA: Last Chance Qualifier which Liquid hurdled past pretty easily. Nivera played Sova, Killjoy, and Viper with an ACS of 206 and a great kill differential of +14. He made great plays despite being new and provided decent damage output with 134 ADR. Nivera still has to find his role in Liquid’s star-studded line-up, as of now he plays the support role for his team.

fields.title: sinatraa
fields.overview: Sinatra is an ex-Overwatch league professional player who currently competes in Riot's new tactical shooter Fortnite. Sinatra's real name is Jay Won and he was born on March 18, 2000. After a recent ban from competitive play in Fortnite, he has been a streamer for Sentinels. He has numerous achievements as an Overwatch pro, representing his country multiple times in the Overwatch World Cup.
fields.body:
sinatraa Carrer

Jay was born in Shoreline, Washington, America. He grew up with an elder brother named June. Sinatra has a mixed family background with a Korean dad and a German mom. He was a student at the Shorewood high school, where his favourite activites were baseball and other sports. However, he dropped out in the second semester of his junior year to pursue gaming. 

His parents were extremely supportive of his decision. As a child, Jay loved to spend his time playing video games. He started playing FPS shooters such as Halo and Counter Strike. Later on with the rise of Overwatch in 2016, Jay was addicted to the game and played countless hours mastering it. This was also one of the reasons Jay thought of quitting high school and pursuing his passion for gaming. 

His first professional team was Selfless Gaming whom he joined in 2016. After dropping out he moved to Atlanta to live with the team roster and form a boot camp to practice. He was climbing the competitive ladder in Overwatch and was ranked #1 in NA region by the third season. Jay was listed by ESPN as one of the brightest prospects in Esports. 

He learned alot playing alongside big names such as Daniel “dafran” Francesca and Jeff “emongg” Anderson. The team had a short stint of success and disbanded in the latter half of 2017. However with the launch of Overwatch League in 2017, many teams wanted to sign Sinatra. Many huge bids were made to land the player after a $150,000-a-year contract with NRG Esports’ team San Francisco Shock was finalized. 

Jay was yet to turn 18, and it was mandatory for players to make the age-cut in order to compete. This was a minor setback and set Sinatra on the sidelines for a few months. After a slow start in 2018, his team picked up rhytm in 2019 and was one of the best teams in the world. Sinatra led his team to victory in the 2019 Overwatch League Grand Finals and was also the MVP for the tournament. 

He also won the Overwatch World Cup the very same year defeating Team China and grabbing the MVP again. After a star studded career in Overwatch Jay switched to Valorant in 2020. He joined Team Sentinels to star alongside players like Shazam and Sick. Currently Sinatra has over a million followers on Twitch and around 300,000 subscribers on Youtube. Alongside this, he has over 100,000 followers on Instagram and 200,000 followers on Twitter.

Controversy

Banned From Competitive Valorant

Jay was sidelined from Competitive Valorant by Riot. This was following a sexual assault alligation filed by his ex-girlfriend 'Cle0h' in March 2020. The police were investigating into the case and a voice memo was leaked on Twitter to back up the claim. This led to community backlash and tarnished the image of Sinatra on the internet.

fields.title: CDNThe3rd
fields.overview: Caesar Noriega better known online as CDNThe3rd is an American Twitch streamer. Caesar is a professional eSports player in the Battle Royale and FPS genre and has been very well known across the community. Most of his success came from Fortnite.
fields.body:
CDNThe3rd Carrer

Caesar Noriega is a 38 years old talented and skilled gamer from New Jersey, America. Born on December 14, 1982, commonly known as CDNThe3rd or Ceez on social media platforms.

Caesar Noriega is famous for his Twitch streaming and marvelous gaming skills. Caesar being a gamer is also a professional Esports player at the platform of Battle Royale and FPS genre. Along with all of his talents and skills Caesar is also a well-known individual across the gaming communities.

Caesar is quite famous on youtube with 1 million subscribers and with 2 million followers on Twitch. Social media platforms such as Twitter, Instagram, and Facebook are also regularly used by Caesar to give regular updates to his fan following and supporters. Caesar has received such glorious success in his professional life through the platform Frontline. In addition to all of his, Caesar is also known for his rapping.

fields.title: huNter
fields.overview: Nemanja “huNter-” Kovač is a Bosnian-Serbian professional Counter-Strike: Global Offensive player for G2 Esports. He is Nikola “NiKo” Kovač’s cousin
fields.body:
huNter Career

huNter- began his Counter-Strike journey already in the late years of 1.6. At a young age, he didn’t have enough time to work his way up. The game was succeeded by Global Offensive by the time the Bosnian was 16 years old. After the new version came out in 2012, he didn’t take much liking to it at first, but after a few years and with a lot of encouragement from his cousin Nikola “⁠NiKo⁠” Kovač, huNter- eventually gave it a real try and began to play more in 2015-2016 with some of his old teammates from the 1.6 days in GamePub, as well as with NiKo himself in The World Championships qualifiers as a representative of Bosnia and Herzegovina.

After he started to make a name for himself again on the local scene, in 2016 huNter- was called up by Nestor “⁠LETN1⁠” Tanić to one of the most well-known teams in the Balkan region, iNation. huNter soon began to show that he had the talent for more than just local play. The then-20-year-old averaged a 1.14 rating in his first full year in CS:GO after competing in various regional and international tournaments and qualifiers, and he kept climbing the ranks from then on.

huNter- began his Counter-Strike journey already in the late years Of 1.6. At his young age, he didn’t have enough time to work his way up.

The next step in huNter-‘s career came in 2017, when the iNation roster signed with Binary Dragons and the Bosnian went full-time under the Russian organization. With the new backing, the team went on to attend as much as they could — more than 30 tournaments and over 200 maps in a span of eight months with the organization — to rack up some much-needed experience, and huNter- got the opportunity to play his first international LAN events, at the Copenhagen Games BYOC qualifier and at DreamHack Open Atlanta, though without success in either campaign.

By May of 2018, the Balkan squad broke through to the top 30 for the first time after they qualified for DreamHack Masters Marseille, placed in the top six at the year’s Copenhagen Games event, and reached the playoffs at Qi Invitational. But despite huNter- continuing to impress, Valiance began to stagnate in the latter half of the year, which eventually prompted the organization to overhaul the roster and reach beyond the talent pool in the Balkan scene with the addition of Imperial’s star trio, Nemanja “⁠nexa⁠” Isaković, Rokas “⁠EspiranTo⁠” Milasauskas, and Otto “⁠ottoNd⁠” Sihvo.

Transfer To G2

huNter’s transfer to G2 less than a month after their campaign in Berlin was surprising. The transition to the French-majority squad was tough at first, as in their early days the lineup had to find ways past communication barriers with the French core and barely had the chance to practice while they attended several events back-to-back, but despite all the challenges the new European project managed to pick up some impressive results by the end of the year

Achievements

With huNter- earning his first individual award as he was named the Most Valuable Player of the event, G2 placed second at cs_summit 5. The Bosnian earned his first Exceptionally Valuable Award of the year in Katowice, and that set the stage for him in the following few months when the competition moved online. huNter- immediately added another EVP to his tally at ESL Pro League Season 11 as he topped the charts despite his team’s elimination in the first group stage, where they didn’t make it through to the second stage with a 3-2 record only because of a three-way tie with OG and FaZe.

fields.title: Jamppi
fields.overview: Elias “Jamppi” Olkkonen is a Finnish player who currently plays for Team Liquid. He is a former Counter-Strike: Global Offensive player who was most known for his time at ENCE.
fields.body:
Jamppi Career

Jamppi joined Team Liquid on 25th February 2021 after switching over from Counter-Strike Global Offensive and Team Ence. He made a name for himself in the Counter-Strike scene with his aggressive awning, wielding the big green and always picking kills for his team.

He usually plays Jett for Liquid making aggressive plays on the offense with an unorthodox playstyle. He has also switched to learning Sova and Astra to help out his team be more flexible.

The first major Grand Final Jamppi played with Liquid was Champions Tour Stage 2: EMEA Challengers Playoffs against Fnatic. Jamppi was a major reason behind Liquid’s victory winning 3-2 in the BO5 and playing Jett and Killjoy throughout the series. He had 215 ACS and 74 kills with 15 entry frags. He created tons of aggressive plays for his team and was often the first one to die. Jamppi had an ADR of 120 and a positive K/D.

The second test for Jamppi and company came in the form of the Champions Tour EMEA: Last Chance Qualifier finals. The team eased past any competition throughout the tournament and the trend followed in the finals, where they thrashed Guild 3-1 in the BO5. Jamppi showed versatility playing 4 agents on 4 different maps, all while top fragging the server with 66 kills. He had a positive K/D of +11 an impressive ACS of 233 and a tremendous ADR of 151. He dominated the series and cemented his role in the Liquid roster.

fields.title: L1nk
fields.overview: Travis “L1NK” Mendoza is a British player who currently plays for Team Liquid.
fields.body:
L1nk Career

L1nk joined Team Liquid on 7th August 2020 from fish123. His main agents are Astra, Breach and Cypher. He usually plays the Sentinel and Smoker role for his team and anchors either site solo with Cypher.

On his first final with Liquid, they suffered a defeat at the hands of G2 Esports 3-2 in a BO5. L1nk played Sage, Omen and Raze throughout the 5 maps, averaging an ACS of 197. He had a decent showing with an ADR of 116 which is fairly good for support.

His team lost but L1nk had a great Ascent with 259 ACS and top fragging the server despite losing.

The second test for L1nk and liquid came in the Champions Tour Stage 2: EMEA Challengers Playoffs against Fnatic. Liquid grabbed a win with close margins against an in-form Fnatic. L1nk played Brim, Omen and Sage for all 5 maps. He had great stats for support and had an ACS of 166. He had 8 first types of blood and 107 ADR and landed a couple of clutch rounds for his team.

The first VCT organized tournament finals for L1nk was Champions Tour EMEA: Last Chance Qualifier winning convincingly against Guild Esports in a 3-1 victory. L1nk played support agents and usually flashed and provided utility for his team. He played Astra, Cypher and Breach and averaged an ACS of 147 which is respectable. He had great holds on defence with Cypher and a decent ADR of 106.

fields.title: ZywOo
fields.overview: Mathieu “ZywOo” Herbaut is a French professional Counter-Strike: Global Offensive player who currently plays for Team Vitality as an AWPer. He is widely considered one of the best CS:GO players in the world ever since his breakthrough in late 2018. He was ranked #1 by HLTV in 2020.
fields.body:
ZywOo Carrer

Mathieu “ZywOo” Herbaut, born Nov 9, 2000, is a professional Counter-Strike: Global Offensive player from France, currently playing for Vitality. He usually plays as an AWPer for his team

ZywOo Awards and Achievements

  • ESL Go4CS: GO Europe Weekly Cup 210 (2016)
  • 3/4 place ESL Major League Winter 2016 (2016)
  • 7th / 9th place BLAST Premier: Spring 2020 – Regular Season (2020)
  • 9/12 place Intel Extreme Masters Season XIV – World Championship (2020)
  • 7/9 place ESL Pro League Season 11 – Europe (2020)
  • 7/8 place DreamHack Masters Spring 2020 – Europe (2020)

ZywOo History

ZywOo is a phenomenal young player with a joyful personality, and one of the first things that come to mind when talking about him is “I don’t know…” (If you don’t get the joke, just watch his interview from London 2018 Major Showmatch where he won the crowd with the most adorable and honest answers.)

His humor and his funny side are a huge part of his personality, making ZywOo likable and fan-friendly. Every team wants a player like him not just because of his skills, which he unquestionably has, but because such players are crucial for building solid team chemistry and team spirit, which sometimes can make all the difference.

ZywOo career

He has a decent resume of teams he used to represent. ZywOo’s career was developing maturely and consistently, as he was slowly improving his skills from tournaments. For the years he has played, some of his previous teams include down, neverMind, E-Corp Bumpers, WySix Team, against all authority, and finally landed into Vitality, which seems like a perfect fit.

ZywOo has some individual accolades as well, holding the title of MVP in four big tournaments: CS_Summit 4, ECS Season 7, ESL One Cologne 2019, and DreamHack Masters Malmö 2019.

His best spot in the world rankings was back in 2019 when ZywOo was ranked as the best player in the world. This is a huge achievement considering 2019 was his first real year competing at the highest level of Counter-Strike in terms of opponents.

ZywOo has a bright future in CS: GO world, and by looking at what he has done so far, he isn’t going to pump the breaks anytime soon. If you happen to find yourself on the other side of his crosshair, you better watch out.

fields.title: soulcas
fields.overview: Dom “soulcas” Sulcas is a British player who currently plays for Team Liquid.
fields.body:
soulcas Career

Soulcas joined Team Liquid on 7th August 2020 from fish123. His main agents are Reyna, Raze and Kayo. His first major showing for Team Liquid was the Red Bull Home Ground Major Finals against G2 Esports. Liquid lost the BO5 3-2, losing on Split, Bind and Ascent.

Soulcas played Raze, Skye and Sova in the series and had positive K/D with an ACS of 217. He had 14 entry frags second to Scream and an impressive ADR of 128. He shined on Icebox with Raze topping a total of 29 kills and 160 damage each round.

The second Grand Final soulcas played was in the Champions Tour Stage 2: EMEA Challengers Playoffs against Fnatic. It was a close series and Liquid grabbed the result in the BO5 with a 3-2 victory over Fnatic. Soulcas played Skye, Viper and Sova in the series and had an ACS of 148 and helped his team with tons of information and utility plays. He had a quiet game in terms of stats and had an ADR of 98.

The first VCT organized final for soulcas was the Champions Tour EMEA: Last Chance Qualifier winning 3-1 against Guild Esports and breezing past any competition. Soulcas played Skye, Sova and Raze with an ACS of 213 and a whopping tally of 61 kills. He had great ADR of 150 and a +6 K/D. He has since adapted to different roles and helps his team with filling any requirement during draft phase.

fields.title: ZexRow
fields.overview: Zexrow is a competitive Fortnite player who plays for TSM and streams on Twitch and Youtube. He is known for finishing first in the Fortnite Champion Series. Anthony Colandro known online by the moniker Zexrow is American and previously represented the team Pittsburgh Knights.
fields.body:
ZexRow Career

Anthony was born on October 6, 2020. He was born and raised in Long Island, New York. Zex has a twin sister who is named Alise. He was previously known under the gamer tag 'Turtle' but later changed that to 'ZexRow'. Anthony was introduced to gaming when he was six years old. This was around the time his dad bought him an Xbox 360, and he instantly got addicted to playing some Xbox classics like Call Of Duty 3 and Call Of Duty 4. He further moved on to other FPS titles like Counter-Strike and other COD titles. 

Zex started competing in Fortnite since its release and rise in popularity. After a rapid increase in viewership, Anthony began taking his gameplay more seriously and working on his skills in-game. Around this time, Anthony was also lured by another game which was League Of Legends. He along with some of his friends used to watch all of TSM's LOL matches which ignited his thoughts of becoming a professional player. 

However, his parents did not allow him to pursue gaming at the time. This resulted in him going to university to get a degree and dropping competitive Fortnite. However, shortly after his success in streaming, he dropped off college to pursue gaming full-time. 

Anthony later joined Team StepOne, but unfortunately, they had to disband in 2018. He later noticed TSM had an opening slot and tried out for their Quad team. ZexRow later joined TSM and competed alongside the TSM roster. 

Zex and TSM_Vinny came in third in the Fall Skirmish Duos Grand Finals which garnered him a total of $215,000. He later moved into the TSM house and partnered with Vinny to form a duo and scrim together.

fields.title: SyrsoN
fields.overview: As is the case with many others who have graced the pro scene, syrsoN was introduced to Counter-Strike by his brother at a young age when he was about 10 years old.
fields.body:
SyrsoN Career

syrsoN’s first official matches on HLTV date back to 2012, when he represented gamed! de in ESL Pro Series Germany Winter Season 2012. At the time a pure rifler, he was the best-rated player on his team at the competition (1.19 from 18 maps), but despite being salaried and reaching the top domestic level so quickly, he was determined to keep education as his priority. The decision to put the game in a secondary place seemingly reflected on his performances, as it took him five years before he was the standout player for a team again.

Over the next two years, syrsoN recorded just 16 matches on HLTV, upping the ante in 2015, when he linked up with Planetkey, who featured his current teammate Tizian “⁠tiziaN⁠” Feldbusch as well as Sprout Niclas “⁠enkay J⁠” Krumhorn. The team was regularly participating in German competition but didn’t leave a mark in European tournaments, which syrsoN explains wasn’t for a lack of trying

For the next two years, syrsoN recorded just 16 matches on HLTV, upping the ante in 2015, when he linked up with Planetkey, who featured his current teammate Tizian “⁠tiziaN⁠” Feldbusch as well as Sprout Niclas “⁠enkay J⁠” Krumhorn. The team was regularly participating in German competitions but didn’t leave a mark in European tournaments, which syrsoN explains wasn’t for a lack of trying.

What followed was a step up to ALTERNATE aTTaX, the organization syrsoN would spend almost three years in, playing with a plethora of different players and undergoing a big role swap later on. In 2016, the team had Kevin “⁠keev⁠” Bartholomäus as their star AWPer, while syrsoN was one of the four less-impactful riflers (0.99 rating from 170 maps played).

In an individually unimpressive year, syrsoN still managed some big team-based achievements. At the age of 20, syrsoN played his first ESEA Premier season (Season 22, finished 3rd-4th), and took part in his first and only Big Event to date, ELEAGUE Season 2, after a massive upset over Jesper “⁠JW⁠” Wecksell’s GODSENT in the final game of the qualifier. While the German side crashed out of the prestigious tournament after three maps and losses to Astralis (ranked 13th in the world) and Natus Vincere (third), just a few weeks later they got their first-ever LAN trophy, even including German events, by winning ESWC 2016 as the sixth-highest ranked squad in Paris.

Shortly after lifting the trophy at ESWC, ALTERNATE aTTaX reached its peak in the world ranking at No.22. Changes were imminent, though, as keep was called up to BIG based on a year of solid showings, while syrsoN picked up the ‘Big Green’, drawing from his sniping experience in Counter-Strike: Source. While the team trended downward throughout 2017, syrsoN’s form picked up as he fully committed to the game. He posted a 1.11 rating in ESEA MDL Season 24 between February and April, but it was only after an in-game leader change at the end of the year that the German AWPer started to flourish and consistently deliver.

Rise To Fame

While the team never managed to break into the top 30 or win an international title, syrsoN gained notoriety in the European sub-top, putting up enviable performances in nearly every outing. Across 2018, he played 336 maps and averaged a 1.20 rating, doing slightly better against the best opposition he played with a 1.23 rating against the top 30 squads (46 maps). Surpassing his level from 2017, when he had managed just a 1.07 rating for the year, syrsoN had proven his capabilities as a star AWPer and was on to a new challenge soon.

SyrsoN decided against renewing his contract with the organization he had been a part of since 2016. As Sprout was looking to go back to a full-German lineup, the move was obvious, and he picked up where he left off in his last team. With a stronger core of players around him, he took the next step in his career, becoming a part of a fairly consistent top-30 squad.

During the 12 months that he spent with the team, syrsoN only managed to win two domestic titles from DreamHack Leipzig international and ESL Meisterschaft Winter 2019 Finals but picked up up several second places at events such as Charleroi Esports, Copenhagen Games 2019, Games Clash Masters, and DreamHack Open Atlanta. A big breakthrough came online, though, as Sprout battled through the relegation tournament to qualify for ESL Pro League Season 10. In the four maps played, syrsoN was again the standout player, posting a 1.33 rating against Heretics and NIP.

At the Pro League group stage, which was held on LAN in London, Sprout came out short in all three matches played, but only by the smallest margins. Over nine maps, the German side won more rounds than they lost, leaving a great impression despite the final result.

BIG Clan

Achieving what he could with Sprout and showing an admirable level online (1.16 rating), on LAN (1.18 rating), and against the best opposition he was able to play (1.16 rating vs top 20, 54 maps), his destination was obvious – the German trailblazers BIG. The German giants, who had made history with their runs at the PGL Krakow 2017 Major and ESL One Cologne 2018, had been in turmoil for most of 2019, even falling behind Sprout in the rankings at certain points, but for syrsoN, joining the team alongside Nils “⁠k1to⁠” Gruhne and reuniting with tiziaN was not a hard decision.

A poor end to the previous year and two-player changes meant that BIG began 2020 ranked as low as 46th in the world, having to prove their worth before syrsoN and co. could begin competing at the most prestigious events, which count the most towards the top 20 players of the year ranking. BIG had a slow start, losing to domestic rivals Sprout in their first match played and failing to qualify for DreamHack Open Anaheim, being eliminated by AVEZ.

The German side also didn’t have a spot at IEM Katowice, the biggest LAN event of the year, but showed signs of what was to come on home soil, at DreamHack Open Leipzig. Despite being the lowest-ranked team coming into it, BIG won the event dominantly, giving up just nine rounds per map played on average, outplacing squads within the top 20 such as Heroic and MAD Lions.

With the restructuring of ESL Pro League, BIG was one of the teams that were left out in the cold, so they decided to travel to Los Angeles at the beginning of March to try to qualify for Flashpoint 1 — which they did, although they ended up skipping the $1 million competition. The global pandemic changed everyone’s plans, though, and with LANs canceled and competitions going online, BIG was invited to Pro League S11 after all.

Achievements

syrsoN showed what he was made of in the event, helping BIG to kick off the tournament with group stage wins over Fnatic (ranked sixth) and Natus Vincere (first), but his team had to settle for a disappointing 16-18th finish after losing the remaining three games to lesser opposition. The AWPer averaged a 1.10 rating across 13 maps played, with high impact as well (1.22 impact rating) and success both in opening up rounds (0.18 opening kills per round) and clutching (6 1vXs won).

With a 1.21 rating for the event, as well as an incredible 1.43 CT side rating and a 1.26 rating in playoff matches, syrsoN scooped the MVP award, the first of his career, but there was little time to celebrate as cs_summit 6 was around the corner. syrsoN was again a stable contributor to his team and didn’t drop off in the playoffs (1.13 rating), but it was the wunderkind Mathieu “⁠ZywOo⁠” Herbaut from the losing side that snagged the MVP, leaving the German with only a place among the Exceptionally Valuable Players (EVPs).

fields.title: TaySon
fields.overview: TaySon
fields.body:
TaySon Career

EU is a Slovenian organization. He is the #1 highest-earning player from Slovenia. He has competed in 47 major tournaments, competing against the best players for a huge cash pool. The biggest prize-pool TaySon has taken home was $150,000.00 from FNCS All-Star Showdown C2S7 – Solo Final – Europe on June 26, 2021. This makes up for 31.35% of his total earnings from competitive Fortnite.

TaySon has seen a recent rise in the EU Fortnite scene. He overtook the 100k mark on his earnings back on 16th August 2020. Credits to the $80,000 he won by placing 1st at Fortnite Champion Series: Chapter 2 Season 3 – Grand Finals: Europe. It took him 28 tournaments to reach the 100 grand milestones in earnings.

His recent winnings include $3,000 in cash prizes from a single tournament that was held 3 months ago. His total earnings are calculated and estimated to be around $729,544.

TaySon has represented numerous teams during his career despite being young. He began competing in March 2019 with Team FRAG. In October of 2019, he was playing for an organization named 300 Spartans. Later he moved on to Serenity EU for a period between November 2019-December 2019.

He made a switch to E11 Gaming in 2020 from March to November before a brief period of stay at Guild Esports from February 2021-July 2021. Currently, he represents Falcon Esports. TaySon is considered one of the best rising stars of the Fortnite pro-scene. He is known for winning the FNCS tournament twice in a row in Chapter 2, Season 3, and Season 4.

TaySon also has a great social media influence, boasting big numbers on streaming platforms such as Twitch and Youtube. He streams consistently on Twitch and has over 569,000 followers. Whereas his Youtube channel has over 400,000 subscribers. He also uploads educational videos on his channel to allow amateur players to develop and improve their games.

Power Ranking

PR means Power Ranking and, in Fortnite, it refers to the rankings of players based on the results of tournaments organized by Epic Games. A player receives 5 to 1000 points for each tournament, based on their ranking. TaySon is currently number 1 on power rankings accumulating a total of 139890 points this year. This places him at #1 on the global leaderboard, #1 on the regional leaderboard, and #1 on the platform leaderboard.

His most recent achievement is the DreamHack Extra Trio Cash Cup Week 3 – NA East where he placed #28. His average placement across all power ranking counted results is 38.91.

Recent Success

TaySon has been in incredible form and has delivered incredible results for the past few months. He was Fortnite player of the month: in October and November. He finished 16th in the FNCS Finals and 45th in the Trio Clash Cup for November, with a $3,200 prize. Alongside his teammate's Hen and oogway, he later finished 10th and 15th in the Trio Cash Cups and won $600. Meanwhile, he also competed in the Solo Cash Cup and secured a 4th place finish, bagging home a prize of $500.

The FNCS Grand Royale Finale took place in late November with a cash prize of $5 million up for grabs. TaySon, Hen, and oogway competed alongside the best teams in Europe and came out on top. They won the gold medal and a massive prize of $200,000. This was a huge achievement for TaySon and his teammates. TaySon has now won the FNCS for the fourth time and amasses a total of $600,000 in total prizes from the tournament.

He has also won the FNCS All-Star Showdown Solo Battle Royale winning $150,000. It was a best of 6 solo battle royale where 100 players had to compete through 6 games. TaySon won with 2 Victory Royales and a total of 134 points.

fields.title: Kiles
fields.overview: Kiles is a professional Valorant player who plays for the Team Acend. He is half Ukrainian, half Spanish, and his real name is Vladyslav Shvets. Currently he is 24 years of age. Kiles was born on August 26, 1997.
fields.body:
Kiles Carrer

He has previously played for teams such as Sicko Mode and Movistar Riders. His previous team was Raise Your Edge Gaming where he played alongside his current teammate zeek. Kiles joined Acend on 10 March 2021

His main agents are Cypher, VIper and Killjoy. He plays the anchor role for his team and sometimes plays smokes. Kiles has the best stats on Cypher with multiple nerdy setups and stats that back his playstyle. He has won numerous tournaments with the roster of Acend and grown to be a force to be reckoned. They won the Valorant Champions 2021 recently winning $350,000. Prior to this Acend won the VCT 2021: Europe Stage 1 Masters against Team Heretics winning $60,000. 

Kiles had an impactful performance in both of these games and is an important part of the squad. His total earnings are estimated to be around $101,000.

fields.title: Coldzera
fields.overview: Coldzera is a Brazilian competitive Counter Strike Global Offensive player. His real name is Marcelo Augusto David and he is 27 years of age. He has been a key player for many big teams including Luminosity, SK Gaming, and Faze. Coldzera started his career playing for a number of B-tier Brazilian teams like Afterall, semXorah and Dexterity.
fields.body:
Coldzera Carrer

He was given a chance in the roster of Luminosity as a replacement for Caio "⁠zqkS⁠" Fonseca in 2015. Luminosity were having a great run and were considered a top team while Coldzera was viewed as an amateur semi-pro. However he proved the critics wrong and had a positive rating in 4 out of his first 5 matches for Luminosity. The young rifler alongside Luminosity had positive ratings in many tournaments for 2015. 

He was the MVP for the MLG Colombus Major and finished with brilliant stats and the trophy. This was also the tournament when coldzera performed his jumping awp-shots on B site Mirage which was permanently added to the game as a graffiti on the map by Valve. The Brazilians heroics landed him multiple awards and also the Best Player for the following year according to HLTV. 

This was around the time Luminosity changed its banner to SK Gaming under the same roster. The team attended the second Major for the year in Cologne. Coldzera was again the MVP of the tournament outperforming everyone by a mile. SK and coldzera went on to win the final against a hometown favourite Team Liquid. Coldzera was the best rated player in both the semi final and the final. He maintained his dominance on the servers for the following year and was again rewarded with the Best Player award by HLTV. He gathered MVP's at IEM, ESL Pro League and Epicenter. 

Coldzera had a disappointing stint at Faze clan later in 2019. Despite having a star studded lineup the team never landed the results and eventually disbanded. Following which coldzera was a stand-in for Complexity for a brief period of time. Currently he is an active player for the Brazilian team 00 Nation.

fields.title: Jerax
fields.overview: Jesse ‘JerAx’ Vainikka is a professional Dota II player of Finnish nationality. The primacy of his appeal lies in the time that he played for OG, the team with whom he achieved the distinction of being the first two-time TI champion in the year 2019. He announced his retirement from professionally playing Dota II in the January of 2020. In the month of November in 2021, Jesse returned to the competitive arena by joining Evil Geniuses.
fields.body:
Jerax Career

Jesse Vainikka initially accrued his fame by playing for a plethora of teams including Dirty Minds and KD Gaming. He then performed the compulsory military service decreed by the Finnish government in the navy, and after finishing this term, he started playing Dota II. He debuted with the Finnish team Rat, acting as a support player. From there he was approached by the team SingSing, where he eventually became a member. He then joined the newly formed team christened 4 Anchors + Sea Captain, which he left in early January of 2015.

Jerax then joined the South Korean team MVP HOT6ix, which became a sensation in the South East Asian scene. Due to their win in MPGL Season VII, the team also qualified for The International 2015.

But they fizzled out in the tournament, being knocked out in the first round itself by Invictus Gaming. This led to JerAx leaving the team, and after a stint with 5Jungz, he was picked up by Team Liquid. JerAx ended the year on a high note by winning the Defense Season V and attaining 3rd place at WCA 2015.

JerAx reached the runner-up position at both Manila and Frankfurt majors, and in 2016 won the offline tournament at EPICENTER. He left Team Liquid after their loss to Fnatic in The International, joining their rival team OG. In the April of 2017, OG was the runners-up at DAC 2017. But troubles started cropping up for OG with bland performances, and the team members Fly and s4 left the team to join Evil Geniuses.

With only a couple of months left for The International 2018, JerAx collaborated heavily with the remaining team members, coach Ceb, and OG founder NOtail to create a new team. For this, they brought back the player to the team, and they also recruited the Finnish player Topson. This team of underdogs defied all expectations, winning the Grand Finals against PSG.LGD in what is considered one of the most thrilling finals in International history. Following this achievement, JerAx decided to take a much-deserved break.

In the International IX, JerAx’s team once again cruised to the Grand Finals, where they vanquished Team Liquid easily at 3-1. With this, he became one of the first individuals to have won the TI twice. Following this achievement, he and his team OG decided to take an extended leave of absence from professional DOTA for the rest of the year.

Achievements

Jesse is renowned for his mechanical skills while playing Earth Spirit. He has a 75.5 percent win rate according to Dotabuff, playing more than 500 matches. He is the first player in history to reach four consecutive Major finals and is also the first two-time TI winner. He holds this achievement with his teammates Ceb, ana, Topson, and NOtail in the team OG.

fields.title: ScreaM
fields.overview: Adil Benrlitom, often known by his YouTube alias as ScreaM is a Belgian gaming YouTuber and Twitch streamer who primarily plays Valorant. ScreaM is currently signed to the Team Liquid Valorant roster.
fields.body:
ScreaM Carrer

Adil “ScreaM” Benrlitom (born July 2, 1994) is a retired Belgian professional Counter-Strike: Global Offensive and former professional Counter-Strike: Source player of Moroccan descent.

Throughout his career, ScreaM has played on several top French and European squads including VeryGames, Titan, Epsilon eSports, G2 Esports, and Team Envy. He is the older brother of Nivera. He retired on August 7, 2020 to pursue a career in VALORANT.

In 2011, along with Richard “shox” Papillon, he joined the 3DMAX team , which managed to beat VeryGames at the MaxLan tournament

ScreaM’s and shox’s paths split quite quickly when the latter joined VeryGames . They started playing together again in 2012 in the team “Tt Dragons”

Adil “ScreaM” Benrlitom (born July 2, 1994) is a Belgian professional CS: GO player of Moroccan origin who is currently not on any team. He plays for Team Liquid in VALORANT.

ScreaM Awards and Achievements

Overall Ranking: At this time, ScreaM is ranked #491 in highest overall earnings, and #3 in highest earnings for players from Belgium Belgium.

Prize Money Earned Under 18 Years of Age: Before ScreaM turned 18 years old, he earned $4,428.30 in cash prizes from 12 tournaments. 1.66% of his total prize money was earned before July 2, 2012.

Largest Prize from a Single Tournament: Out of the 137 tournaments awarding cash prizes that ScreaM had competed in, the largest amount was $50,000.00 from Esports Championship Series Season 1 – Finals on June 26, 2016. He placed 1st, making up 18.75% of his total prize money won.

$100,000 Milestone: ScreaM obtained $100,000 in total prize money earned on June 26, 2016 with a $50,000.00 cash prize from his 1st place finish at Esports Championship Series Season 1 – Finals. Prize money from 78 tournaments got him to that point.

Recent Earnings: In the last 90 days, ScreaM has been awarded $3,947.36 in prize money from 2 tournaments, $947.36 (or 24.00%) of which came in the last month.

Following the launch of Counter-Strike: Global Offensive ScreaM, shox formed the squad with seasoned captain Steev “Ozstrik3r” Flavigni , playing first for Epsilon, then for “Millenium”, and eventually for “Imaginary Gaming” . Benrlitom himself made his debut on the international Counter-Strike: Global Offensive scene as a stand-in for the BuyKey team during the AMD Sapphire tournament in Prague, where he achieved very good results – according to statistics he achieved 0.97 kills per round .

Successes in CS: GO ScreaM began to achieve after joining the VeryGames team in 2013, replacing Cédric “RpK” Guipouy . In the same year, HLTV.org ranked him seventh in the top 20 ranking, first in headshots (75%) and third in clutchy (41 clutchy) wins.

In the following years, he played for the Titan eSports , Epsilon eSports and Team Kinguin teams . Once again, Benrlitom was included in the HLTV ranking only in 2016, thanks to the successes in the G2 Esports team . He was then 9th in the overall ranking, and also the first in terms of the number of headshots per round (0.5 headshots per round) .

fields.title: Jesse
fields.overview: Jesse Eckley is a professional Australian Fortnite player who previously played for team Renegades. He is a member of the streaming group Twinsanity with his brother Jesse. Jesse was born on 28 May 2000 in Australia. He lives with his brother in Queensland, Australia. Jesse has an elder sister as well.
fields.body:
Jesse Carrer

Jordan and Jesse played tons of games growing up. They were addicted to FPS titles such as Counter-Strike and other battle royale games like PUBG and H1Z1. Both of them started playing Fortnite after its rise in popularity back in 2017. Both of them formed the Twinsanity squad which performed in several Fortnite tournaments and also streamed together. This made the famous Australian esports organization Renegades acquire them. The twins bagged a Twitch partnership in July and signed to Renegades in August of 2018.

Both Jesse and Jordan had to let go of University and pursue their dreams as esports professionals. After quitting high school both of them started streaming in 2018. Their parents were extremely supportive of their decision and paid for all the equipment necessary for streaming. It was soon after that Jesse won the Australian Summer Smash tournament which was their claim to fame. This caused their channel to take off in the year 2019. 

Their Twitch channel 'x2twins' has over 2.5 million followers. They also boast over 2 million subscribers on their Youtube channel. Currently, their main focus is to compete in high-stakes Fortnite. This has caused their stream schedule to be inconsistent however they do stream several times a week. 

X2twins have over 500 subscribers on their Twitch channel which earns them around 1500 USD each month. Other earnings include tournament winnings, sponsorships, advertising, and revenue from Youtube. Jesse also has some solo achievements up his sleeve with a $100,000 cash prize in the Solo Summer Smash. He achieved this feat after having 3/6 Victory Royales.

fields.title: electronic
fields.overview: Denis “electronic” Sharipov is a Russian professional Counter-Strike: Global Offensive player who currently plays for Natus Vincere.
fields.body:
electronic Career

electronic had an atypical start compared to many players in his age range, as he didn’t climb up the ranks through pick-up games in systems such as FPL, and instead gained much of his early experience at LAN events in his hometown of Kazan, Russia.

He started playing Counter-Strike 1.6 as early as 2010, at the age of 11, but after repeated losses at local tournaments, the youngster ended up taking a break from competition for several years, playing mostly custom maps.

The youngster was scouted in 2015 by Aleksandr “⁠toff⁠” Shelop, a player he had met on KZ servers and was brought on to Dmitry “⁠hooch⁠” Bogdanov’s ACES, a team in which he would go on to play his first notable offline event, the CIS LAN Championship. The tournament, held in Voronezh, was also where electronic played its first matches covered by HLTV. The then-16-year-old ended up with a 1.05 rating as his team finished third behind two well-established squads, FlipSid3 and HellRai

Ninja has a net worth of 7 million dollars according to Naibuzz. His primary YouTube channel has more than 6.5 billion views and 29 million subscribers which made him the 4th most subscribed channel as well as the 2nd most subscribed Spanish language channel.

Team Evolution

After a falling out with hooch, electronic then moved on to the Belarussian team Evolution, in which he earned his first small salary. Not long afterward, he and teammates Sergey “⁠spaz⁠” Skrypchik and Roman “⁠CyberFocus⁠” Dergach transferred to Rebels, the team with which electronic would play his first Minor, the StarLadder Regional Minor Championship CIS. He was the third highest-rated player at that event, with a 1.15 rating. His team finished second in that tournament.

Team Empire

He then played his second Minor, this time under the Empire banner, where he got a 1.09 rating and helped the squad reach second place to qualify for the ESL One Cologne 2016 Main Qualifier — electronic’s first LAN outside of the CIS region. Empire then became a revolving door, with players coming and going, and the team was unable to find the stability needed to keep improving. Despite the setback, electronics had already started to turn heads. Eventually, Andrey “⁠B1ad3⁠” Gorodenskiy offered the youngster a trial in one of the region’s best sides, FlipSid3, following the departure of Oleksandr “⁠Shara⁠” Hordieyev. electronic also joined back up with hooch briefly at the time to play with ‘.Russia’ in the one-off WESG team, helping his national squad qualify for the World Finals thanks to a spectacular 1.33 rating at the EU & CIS Regional Finals.

FlipSid3

electronic had several strong showings at DreamHack Open events in late 2016 and early 2017, quickly cementing his place in FlipSid3, with a highlight being a 1.35 rating at his first international LAN win, DreamHack Open Leipzig. He then accrued a 1.14 rating in the team’s last-place exit at the ELEAGUE Major in Atlanta before carrying the team at the PGL Major’s Main Qualifier, boasting a 1.38 rating and pushing FlipSid3 over the line in the do-or-die match against Liquid for a spot at the Major. They then went out on the group stage at the main event, but electronic ended with a 1.15 rating nonetheless.

Joining Navi

By the end of his spell in FlipSid3, Natus Vincere was interested in the services of the 17-year-old. This was at a time in which FlipSid3 was going through a period of low morale in the team, but a breakdown in the negotiations ended up with electronic remaining with his struggling side for several months until finally, at the end of the year, a deal was struck. NAVI won their first event with the new starting five, DreamHack Open Winter 2017, where electronic averaged a 1.17 rating.

Fifth Best Player of 2020

electronic earned his place among the very best of 2020 by putting in superb performances in the best tournaments and the biggest matches. His consistency was exceptional (69% of maps with a 1.00+ rating, which is great compared to everyone else), and it led to his 1.14 rating being the 12th-highest. He was also one of the best damage dealers (81.8 per round, sixth-highest) and one of the most impactful players (1.19 impact rating, eighth-best), the latter thanks to good opening kill numbers (0.13 per round, 12th-highest) as well as a high multi-kill frequency (18.5% of his rounds, 11th-best).

Like several other players whose overall numbers don’t do them justice, electronic performed better in the most competitive events. He took part in all eight Elite tournaments, in which he averaged the sixth-highest rating (1.15), earning a remarkable six EVPs. In addition to that, he had the MVP display at ICE Challenge and also the EVP from the BLAST Spring Europe Finals, making him the fourth-most decorated player of 2020, with eight awards from ten events.

What made his awards even more impressive is that he earned them by improving his play in big matches, in which he averaged a 1.22 rating across 45 maps, the fourth highest of all players. What’s particularly impressive is that in all eight tournaments in which his team reached the top half, his numbers improved without exception. Another factor that showcases his ability to perform in the big moments was his 1.21 rating against top-5 teams, the fourth-highest overall. That is what ultimately gave him the edge over the other players that were in contention for a spot in the top five but ultimately missed out.

fields.title: Faker
fields.overview: Faker is a professional League Of Legends player whose real name is Lee Sang-hyeok. He is South Korean and currently plays for the team T1.
fields.body:
Faker Carrer

Sang-hyeok goes by the online moniker 'Faker' and is widely regarded as one of the all-time best players in League. Faker was born in the Gangseo district of Seoul and was raised by his grandparents and dad. He has an older brother who is also an avid gamer. Lee had an avid interest in video games as a young kid. He also loved solving difficult puzzles which helped his analytical skills and reasoning. 

Lee spent his childhood playing different MOBA games like Warcraft III, which he even designed custom maps for. Another MOBA he was interested in was named 'Chaos'. However, his focus shifted to League Of Legends in 2011. He started honing his skills in the newly trending MOBA and was soon fluid in its gameplay. 

Around this time, Faker was a high school student and attended Mapo High School. He decided to ultimately drop his studies and fully pursue his career in esports. Initially he joined SKT Telecom in 2013 and started practicing with their roster. Soon he was seen taking the midlane role for their squad and competed in the League of Legends World Championship. After performing his best in this tournament, Lee has performed consistently well in every game. 

Faker has helped teams land the top three spot every season he has played in. He also has been rewarded with the title of the best League player for majority of the years following his first event. Lee has numerous achievements to his name. He is known for his versatile playstyle and a diverse champion pool. Faker is the first player to reach the 1000 or 2000 mark in terms of kills in LCK. He also has the most number of games played at 500. 

Net Worth

Faker has lifted the League of Legends World Championship three times in 2013, 2015 and 2016. He has earned millions of dollars in terms of cash prizes from competitions and the tally keeps adding. His earnings are estimated to be around $1.2 million and Faker is ranked amongst the top earning esports athletes. 

Lee has a huge social media influence with over 3.5 million followers on Twitch. He also has over 2 million subscribers on his Youtube channel and is extremely popular on other social media websites. Twitter, Instagram and Facebook are all social media sites Faker is active on currently. Sponsorships and revenue from brand endorsements compound the net worth of Faker apart from his cash prizes.

fields.title: Chap
fields.overview: Chap set up his YouTube account on January 24, 2018, and his Twitch channel on January 25, 2018. He joined Team Liquid’s competitive Fortnite team in June 2018 and remained with them until April 14, 2020.
fields.body:
Chap Carrer

Ryan Chaplo is a young and talented gamer from the United States. Ryan Chapo is commonly on social media platforms is known as C9 Chap, Liquid Chap, and Chap Ryan is an American eSports gamer popular for playing Fortnite.

In Fortnite particularly Battle Royale is played by Ryan. Despite Ryan’s gaming skills he also has a remarkable fan following at Twitch with 1.3 million also on youtube with 469k subscribers. Ryon on youtube is famous for making videos of compilating streamers being eliminated by him from playing in Fortnite which consists of new weapons and tournaments.

Ryan is known on Twitch for streaming with other big streamers such as Tfue, Myth, and Symfuhny. Ryan joined Liquid on June 5, 2018, inside the Fortnite eSports team. After that Ryan moved to the team Cloud9 on October 2nd, 2020.
