Ryan Chaplo commonly famous as Chap is one of the most dedicated members of Team Cloud9. Ryan has parted ways with the organization. It’s challenging to think of a pro player who can be more synonymous with an organization than Ryan ‘Chap’.

Ryan is a professional streamer and Fortnite player along with his combination of regular Twitch streams and YouTube compilation videos. Ryan has quickly risen to be one of the top Fortnite streamers and players in the world. In the time span of one year, Ryan has amassed a tremendous following, joined two esports teams and participated in 19 different tournaments, and got the top spot on several occasions.

Despite being a member of Team Liquid, which is regularly considered to be within the Top 5 teams in the world. Ryan also keeps his personal life fairly private.

fields.title: Khanada
fields.overview: Khanada is an American Fortnite streamer whose real name is Leon Khim. He is known for his Fortnite gameplay and has racked up more than 400,000 followers on his Twitch.
fields.body:
Khanada career

Khanada started gaining traction and relevancy on Youtube and Twitch around 2018. With the rise of Fortnite in popularity Khanada and his channel grew in subscribers. His content was unique and entertaining. Khanada is extremely skillful and talented in battle royale games and this helped him shine in Fortnite. 

Leon was born on 15th October 2004 and is 16 years of age as of now. He is extremely young and influences a lot of teenagers to be like him. Khanada is active on all his social and posts regularly. He has around 240,000 followers on Instagram. Leon also has a Twitter handle to his name titled "@Khanada".

His biggest achievements include a fourth-place finish in the FNCS Invitational Grand Finals: NA East held in 2020. Khanada was previously affiliated with the gaming organization Chronic. He is a three-time solo cash cup winner. 

Net Worth 

Khanada has competed in a total of 32 tournaments. Most of his net worth comprises cash awards and prizes he has won in these tournaments. His biggest prize was $35,000 from the fourth placement in FNCS Grand Finals. This constitutes 1/4th of Leon's net worth.

He surpassed the 100k milestone after placing 10th in the Fortnite Champion Series and winning 2.6k dollars. It took him 26 tournaments to reach the milestone. His net worth is estimated to be around $500,000 including revenue from Twitch and Youtube. He has won total prize money of around $142,000 from a total of 32 tournaments.

Fortnite Ban

Khanada is known to be aggressive in-game while taunting his opponents and hurling abuse. Due to this, he was banned from Twitch back in September during a Fortnite Wager match. Twitch issued a statement that pointed out that Khanada took his trash-talking too far. His violent threats during the stream leave a bad impression on the spectators. 

He tried to appeal for an unban but was later denied by Twitch. It was after this incident that Khanada had to part ways with TSM. He later joined the esports org named Built By Gamers.

fields.title: nAts
fields.overview: Ayaz “nAts” Akhmetshin is a Russian player who is currently playing for Gambit Esports. He is a former Counter-Strike: Global Offensive player.
fields.body:
nAts Career

NAts was a former Counter-Strike veteran and an experienced player picked up by Gambit Esports on 28th September, 2020 from FishkaVTom. He has since created a name for himself in the Valorant scene playing anchor for Gambit on agents like Cypher and Viper. NAts does not show up on the kill feed with his playstyle but his utility and information provides great help to his team. His solo B site holds and impact kills have often bailed out Gambit from tough scenarios’.

The first major Grand Final with nAts and Gambit was the Nicecactus Summer Trophy #2. Gambit won 2-0 against HSDIRR and nAts was on Cypher for both maps.

He had impenetrable setups on both Bind and Split which secured his team many rounds on the defence. He had an ACS of 199 and ADR of 133 but his impact showed when it was most needed. Always at the right place at the right time for his team, nAts welcomed enemies and shredded through them on his setups.

The next Major Grand Final was the NGL Open Cup, although Gambit lost 2-1 to Opportunists nAts cemented his position in the roster with a great showing. He played Cyoher on all three maps (Bind, Haven and Split) and outfragged everyone except rodeN(53 kills) with 52 kills. He had amazing hold and at times it felt like the tide was on Gambit’s favour, but a trail of rounds assured the victory for Opportunists. NAts had an ACS of 238 and 144 ADR in the series.

NAts then went on to win 2 VCT hosted tournaments with Gambit. Champions Tour CIS Stage 1: Masters, winning 3-0 against forZe and Valorant Champions Tour Stage 3: Masters Berlin winning 3-0 against Envy. NAts had a great showing on both the series playing his usual Cypher and Viper. He is regarded as one of the best Anchor/Sentinel players in the CIS region

fields.title: Zfreek
fields.overview: Zakari William Lee “Zfreek” Freedman is a professional Dota 2 player from the United States who currently represents the 4 Zoomers.
fields.body:
Zfreek Career

Before DreamHack Winter 2011, Zfreek was invited by his brother, Kyle, to join Trademark eSports and compete in competitive HoN. Stay Green was created in 2012 by him and his brother. He won many events with Stay Green, including the HoN Tour Seasons 1 and 2, and he and his brother were the only players to win five straight major LAN titles.

Swindlemelonzz, Zfreek, Khezu, Skyzoe, and Sender were the original members of Team stay green; when Skyzoe and Sender left, Chessie and SlickZ were added. stayGreen went on to win five consecutive major LAN tournaments (after two of them, Khezu and Slickz were replaced by Limmp and Mynuts), breaking Fnatic's record, and then split in early 2014. He stayed with this team until mid-2014 when he and his brother switched to Dota 2.

Heroes of Newerth

Before DreamHack Winter 2011, Zfreek was invited by his brother, Kyle, to join Trademark eSports and compete in competitive HoN. Stay Green was created in 2012 by him and his brother. He won many events with Stay Green, including the HoN Tour Seasons 1 and 2, and he and his brother were the only players to win five straight major LAN titles. Swindlemelonzz, Zfreek, Khezu, Skyzoe, and Sender were the original members of Team stay green; when Skyzoe and Sender left, Chessie and SlickZ were added. stayGreen went on to win five consecutive major LAN tournaments (after two of them, Khezu and Slickz were replaced by Limmp and Mynuts), breaking Fnatic's record, and then split in early 2014. He remained with his team until he transitioned to Dota 2 with his brother in mid-2014.

Dota 2

StayGreen was the moniker of their first Dota 2 team, which was later acquired by compLexity Gaming in August 2014. A year later, the team competed in their first TI, finishing 9-12th despite a good group stage. Zfreek’s attendance at the TI would be his last. CoL was eliminated in the Wild Cards at TI6, and he failed to qualify the following years.
After a string of poor outcomes, his brother has kicked off the team in early 2018, after more than three years of playing together on CoL. Zfreek kept working on coL for another year. It would be his first time playing without his sibling in his career. Complexity dropped their entire squad, including Zfreek, after failing to qualify for The International 2019. For the previous four years, he had been a member of the team.

He joined OG Seed after leaving Complexity. “OG Seed” was OG’s second squad, developed in the months following the 2019 International. Madara, Chessie, Xibbe, and Peksu were among the group. Zfreek eventually left the company for TOOBASED, a North American squad that was created during the DPC 2021 season. Along with Flee, Empyrean, and Sup, he played position 4.

Controversy

Kyle “melonzz” Freedman, a former compLexity Gaming teammate, is Zfreek’s brother. He turned to rejected offers from other teams to join his sibling on the team. With the roster of Moonmeander, Riser, Zfreek, Swindlemelonzz, and Limp, they entered the scene together and were picked up by Complexity Gaming. However, on March 16th, 2018, Complexity Gaming confirmed Kyle’s departure, citing “Personality disputes within the squad were too severe to continue,” as the cause. Zfreek exited the Complexity lineup shortly after.

fields.title: cNed
fields.overview:
Mehmet YaÄŸÄ±z Ä°pek is a Turkish player playing for Acend.

“cNed” as he is best known, is one of the most popular players in Valorant Turkey. His older brother, a professional Counter-Strike player introduced him to Gaming at the age of six.
fields.body:
cNed Career

As a result, cNed was exposed to a wide range of games from a young age, but it was first-person shooters that piqued his interest, and after purchasing his first computer, he embarked on his first FPS journey with Counter-Strike. cNed has proved his abilities in a variety of competitive games since turning pro, and his esports experience, which began with Counter-Strike and continued with Zula, has recently seen him make a successful transfer to Valorant.

By finishing runner-up in the European Region at the Twitch Rivals Valorant Showdown 2020 and qualifying with his team for the Valorant First Strike European Finals 2020, he soon gained attention in Valorant, both domestically and internationally.

On March 10th, 2021, CNed joined the Acend Valorant lineup from Raise Your Edge Gaming. Raise Your Edge Gaming was an esports team based in Europe that was later renamed Acend. Santeri ‘BONECOLD’ Sassi, Vladyslav ‘Kiles’ Shvets, and Patryk’starxo’ Kopczynski, all former CNed colleagues, were scouted into Acend. Jett and Sage are CNed’s principal agents

Raise Your Edge Gaming

Champions Tour Europe Stage 1: Challengers 1

Under the name Raise Your Edge Gaming, CNed only entered one tournament. Up until the round of 32, all Challengers 1 matchups were BO1s. For CNed, the BO1s was a breeze, as he breezed past TwistedMinds and Prophecy ESC. In RO32, FunPlus Phoenix presented the first genuine challenge. In the series, CNed faced Jett and Raze, but they were defeated 2-0 by FunPlus. With a K/D of +7, CNed was the only player on his side with a positive K/D. He had 43 frags throughout the course of two maps, leading his team to victory on both occasions. He had an ADR of 170 and 8 First Kills on average.

CNed and the team responded with a 2-0 win over Team Vitality. CNed played Jett on both maps and had a lot of mid-round influence with the Operator. On the side of Raise Your Edge, his relentless sniper netted him a number of kills and rounds. CNed was second to none with 39 kills, outflagging the server by a razor-thin margin. He had 9 first kills and a +6 kill-to-death ratio. This was his breakthrough performance, establishing him as a European talent. He had an ADR of 148 on average.

Then, in the Quarter Finals, Raise Your Edge went on a winning spree, defeating SAW, Rix.GG, and even OG. It was unexpected to see a team of young amateurs defeat OG 2-0 in a BO3 match. It might be stated that RYE Gaming deserved to win because they didn’t even need CNed to do so. CNed had 26 kills and a respectable ADR of 132 in the 2-0 win over Ascent and Bind. He provided entries for his squad on Attack and was generally the first person to enter each location, aside from a decent score sheet.

Acend

Champions Tour Europe Stage 1: Masters
With the acquisition of Aleksander ‘zeek’ Zygmunt, the team later changed its name to Acend. They won the VCT EU S1 Masters and received a cash prize of $60,000. The team went on a tear after losing 2-0 to Ninjas In Pajamas in the Opening Main Event, going undefeated for the rest of the tournament. In the knockout match, Acend defeated Ballista 2-0, with CNed leading his side from the front on his Jett. He was simply invincible against a squad of novices, with 35 kills and a +22 Kill Differential.

Acend then went on to win the Decider 2-0 over the Ninjas. With his distinctive agent, CNed was once again guiding his squad to the front. This time, though, he was assisted by BONECOLD, the best player on the server. He had an ACS of 280 and a headshot percentage of 40%.

In the Semi-finals, Acend defeated FunPlus Phoenix in a similar fashion. This was a tough match that went the distance, necessitating a third map decider to separate the two sides. In the series, CNed had 67 kills and put up a dominant effort to help his team win and advance to the Grand Finals. He had a +19 K/D and 180 ADR, according to his stats. In addition, he had 11 First Kills.

Grand Finals

Acend and Team Heretics battled it out in a best-of-five match in the Grand Final. It was a tight final between two high-caliber teams that pushed one other to their maximum. The game went the distance, as Acend finally defeated Ascent 13-11 to claim the title of Grand Champions. CNed recorded 111 kills and a positive K/D of +30 in the Grand Finals, easily his best performance on the grandest stage of his career. He had 21 First Kills and annihilated the Heretics’ defence. His kills were complimented by a 277 ACS and a 170 ADR.

Acend had reached its pinnacle as a team and a force to be reckoned with at this point. They have yet to land a second VCT Master, having fallen to Vitality in the quarterfinals earlier this year. Then there was the loss in the Berlin Masters QF to 100 Thieves. They are currently competing in the VCT: Champions and have won two group stage matches.

Controversies

Scam of Turkish Money Laundering “cNed” pek, admitted to being engaged in the Twitch money laundering incident on broadcast. Riot Games is investigating several Turkish VALORANT pros who have been implicated in the issue. The scandal involves consumers donating significant sums of money to streamers using stolen credit cards, with the streamers splitting the money with the donors.

According to cNed, he never had direct contact with the scandal’s mastermind, but was instead linked to him through his brother, Alihan “deNc” pek. CNed further stated that one of the strategies employed by the offender to persuade streamers to split the money was threatening to contribute so many bits that Twitch would shut down their channel permanently and take away all earnings, as he claimed to have witnessed with a friend.

There is no word yet on whether this issue will have an impact on his team’s standing.

fields.title: s1mple
fields.body:
s1mple Carrer

S1mple was born in Kyiv, Ukraine. He started playing Counter-Strike at four years old at the recommendation of his older brother. S1mple picked up Counter-Strike: Global Offensive shortly after its release in 2012, joining his first professional team a year later.

S1mple’s first team was a team called LAN DODGERS, but he was soon signed by Courage Gaming. Around September 2014, s1mple was signed by a large organization known as Hellraisers. There, he joined ANGE1, Dosia, Kucher, and Markeloff, who s1mple considers his idol

In January 2015, s1mple was soon removed from Hellraisers due to his inflammatory comments about Germans, and an ESL wire ban for cheating. This ban was also extended to 2016 due to ban evasion.

In 2016, After a short stint studying Chinese at a university, s1mple moved to America in early 2016 and joined Team Liquid. A Team Liquid player, Spencer “Hiko” Martin, was standing in for Flipsid3 at ESWC 2015, and he developed a friendly relationship with s1mple there. Team Liquid was surprised at the first major, and reached the semifinals of MLG Major Championship: Columbus, before falling to the eventual champions, Luminosity Gaming.

In 2019, Na’Vi came 3rd to 4th in the first major of the year. S1mple would keep up his form from 2018, and receive an MVP at StarSeries Season 7. After this, Na’Vi would eventually hit a slump and replace s1mple’s long time teammate Ioann “Edward” Sukhariev with Kirill “Boombl4” Mikhailov who was in September 2019 made the team’s leader

Oleksandr Kostyliev better known as s1mple, is a Ukrainian professional Counter-Strike: Global Offensive player for Natus Vincere. He is considered to be one of the best players in Global Offensive history. he is 22 years old and was born on 2 October 1997.

S1mple Awards and Achievements

Rankings

HLTV Top 20 Players:

4th 2016
8th 2017
1st 2018
2nd 2019

MVP

  • DreamHack Winter 2017
  • StarSeries Season 4, 2018
  • StarSeries Season 5, 2018
  • ESL One Cologne 2018
  • Dreamhack Masters Marseille 2018
  • CS: GO Asia Championships 2018
  • BLAST Pro Series Copenhagen 2018
  • StarSeries Season 7, 2019
  • IEM Katowice 2020

EVP

  • FACEIT Major: London 2018
  • MLG Major Championship: Columbus, 2016
  • ESL One Cologne 2016
  • IEM Katowice 2019

Other awards

  • Esports Awards, PC Player of the Year, 2018

S1mple Teams History

2013-10-06 – 2014-02-11 Ukraine LAN DODGERS
2014-02-12 – 2014-04-13 Ukraine Courage Gaming
2014-04-14 – 2014-04-29 Ukraine hashtag
2014-04-29 – 2014 Ukraine LAN DODGERS
2014 – ?? – ?? – 2014-09-09 Ukraine Amazing Gaming
2014-09-18 – 2015-01-14 Ukraine Hellraisers
2015-01-15 – 2015-02-01 Ukraine dAT Team
2015-02-01 – 2015-07-17 Ukraine Flipsid3 Tactics
2015-07-20 – 2015-07-26 Ukraine Evolution
2015-07-26 – 2015-08-25 Ukraine Evolution.Dark
2015-08-25 – 2015-09-10 Ukraine Worst Players
2015-09-13 – 2015-10-22 Ukraine HellRaisers (Temporary)
2015-12- ?? – 201? – ?? – ?? Ukraine Flipsid3 Tactics (Temporary)
2016-01-02 – 2016-04-20 USA Team Liquid
2016-04-20 – 2016-05-08 USA Team Liquid (reserve)
2016-05-08 – 2016-06-02 Ukraine Worst Players
2016-06-06 – 2016-08-04 USA Team Liquid
2016-08-04 – still CIS Natus Vincere

S1mple Early life

S1mple was born in Kyiv, Ukraine. He started playing Counter-Strike at four years old at the recommendation of his older brother. S1mple picked up Counter-Strike: Global Offensive shortly after its release in 2012, joining his first professional team a year later.

S1mple Career

2014

S1mple’s first team was a team called LAN DODGERS, but he was soon signed by Courage Gaming. Around September 2014, s1mple was signed by a large organization known as Hellraisers.

There, he joined ANGE1, Dosia, Kucher, and Markeloff, who s1mple considers his idol.

2015

In January 2015, s1mple was soon removed from Hellraisers due to his inflammatory comments about Germans, and an ESL wire ban for cheating. This ban was also extended to 2016 due to ban evasion. S1mple himself says that the ban was from cheating in Counter-Strike 1.6. The global offensive community has however raised doubts about the ban being from CS 1.6. There are claims stating that there is evidence that the ESL wire ban is from Counter-Strike Global Offensive. No comments regarding this have been made from ESL. S1mple was soon after signed by Flipsid3 Tactics, but his time in the team would be cut short due to the team’s semi-final exit at ESWC 2015. Contrary to his teammates, s1mple wasn’t happy about the result. At this period in his career, s1mple was known for being quite “toxic,” or rude to his teammates.

2016

After a short stint studying Chinese at a university, s1mple moved to America in early 2016 and joined Team Liquid. A Team Liquid player, Spencer “Hiko” Martin, was standing in for Flipsid3 at ESWC 2015, and he developed a friendly relationship with s1mple there. Team Liquid was surprised at the first major, and reached the semifinals of MLG Major Championship: Columbus, before falling to the eventual champions, Luminosity Gaming. Despite this result at the game’s biggest tournament, it wouldn’t be long before s1mple would leave Team Liquid, citing homesickness. The next major of the year was approaching, and s1mple once again played for Team Liquid. During the semifinals at ESL One Cologne 2016, Valve Corporation added graffiti on Cache commemorating s1mple’s falling AWP play against Fnatic. Thus, Team Liquid became the first North American team to reach a major final. They were stopped in the finals by the same Brazilian lineup of SK (formerly Luminosity Gaming). After leaving Team Liquid, he replaced Danylo “Zeus” Teslenko on Natus Vincere.

With Na’Vi, s1mple won ESL One: New York 2016, and he was awarded the #4 placement in the HLTV top 20.

2017

During the first major of the year, ELEAGUE Major 2017, Na’Vi lost to Astralis during the quarterfinals. After a group stage exit at PGL 2017 Krakow Major Championship, Na’Vi benched Ladislav “GuardiaN” Kovacs and Denis “seized” Kostin former-member Danylo “Zeus” Teslenko. GuardiaN had been the AWPer for Na’Vi, so s1mple was forced to take up the sniper rifle after his departure. Despite these changes, Na’Vi continued their drought of results and found a replacement for seized in the form of Denis “electronic” Sharipov. s1mple didn’t find much success in 2017, but he still kept up his form from the last year. S1mple was awarded the #8 placement in the HLTV top 20 this year, down from #4 in 2016 due to a lack of results in the team

2018

NAVi started 2018 with a semi-final finish at ELEAGUE Major: Boston 2018. At the start of 2018, Brazilian organization MIBR attempted to sign s1mple and flamie. The deal was reportedly very close to being finished, but Na’Vi asked for too high of a buyout, and the deal eventually fell through. After two 2nd-place finishes at Starladder & i-League StarSeries Season 4 and Dreamhack Masters Marseille, Na’Vi won their first event of the year at StarSeries & i-League Season 5; they would follow it up with wins at CAC 2018, and ESL One Cologne 2018. S1mple won MVPs at StarSeries and Dreamhack Marseille, despite his team not winning the events. In the semifinals at Cologne, they beat the best team at the time, Astralis. Na’Vi would lose to Astralis at the second major of the year, FACEIT Major: London 2018. Na’Vi won their final event of the year, BLAST Pro Series: Copenhagen 2018, and s1mple would once again claim the MVP award. Due to s1mple’s performance, he would be nominated for the #1 spot in the HLTV top 20 players of 2018. According the to statistics from HLTV, s1mple in 2018 had achieved the highest individual rating out of all previous top 20 players. He is considered one of the best players to ever play Counter-Strike.

2019

Na’Vi came 3rd to 4th in the first major of the year. S1mple would keep up his form from 2018, and receive an MVP at StarSeries Season 7. After this, Na’Vi would eventually hit a slump and replace s1mple’s long-time teammate Ioann “Edward” Sukhariev with Kirill “Boombl4” Mikhailov who was in September 2019 made the team’s leader (or IGL).

fields.title: Dakotaz
fields.overview: Brett Hoffman better known online as Dakotaz, is an American Twitch Streamer, YouTuber, and a professional Fortnite player. Brett streams on Twitch every day and uploads on YouTube almost every day.
fields.body:
Dakotaz Carrer

Brett has a twin brother who goes by his own alias ‘Drnkie’. He is also a Twitch Streamer.

Brett stumbled upon PUBG, gaining partial success off of it before the release of Fortnite. Brett only enveloped 100,000 Twitch followers and 92,000 subscribers on YouTube before Fortnite.

TSM (Team SoloMid) is an eSports team that Dakotaz joined alongside HighDistortion on January 11, 2018. Exactly 1 year later, Dakotaz decided to leave TSM of his own will and see what would happen for the rest of 2019

Dakotaz is a popular gaming YouTuber and Twitch streamer from the United States. He has an estimated net worth of $2.5 million.

Brett Hoffman better known online as Dakotaz (also known as Dark and initialized as DK), is an American Twitch Streamer, YouTuber, and a professional Fortnite player. Brett streams on Twitch every day and uploads on YouTube almost every day commentating and making gameplays on something that is recently added to Fortnite and/or the moments, notably snipes. He is 34 years old and was born on July 13, 1986.

Dakotaz Awards and Achievements

2018-10-28 5th Team-based Tournament Fortnite Fall Skirmish Series Clubs Standings $2,500.00 Fortnite

Dakotaz History

Brett began streaming the month he created his YouTube channel. He emerged from uploading gameplay videos of Infestation: Survivor Stories (formerly known as The War Z) featuring funny moments, announcements, and clips. He gained over 30,000 subscribers from Infestation videos before moving on to H1Z1 and has gained a reputation while doing so. Brett stumbled upon PUBG, gaining partial success off of it before the release of Fortnite. Brett only enveloped 100,000 Twitch followers and 92,000 subscribers on YouTube before Fortnite. Fortnite puts him in the position he is at now for his gameplay, commentaries, and snipes.

Dakotaz Personal Life

Brett has a twin brother who goes by his own alias ‘Drnkie’. He is also a Twitch Streamer.

Dakotaz TSM

TSM (Team SoloMid) is an eSports team that Dakotaz joined alongside HighDistortion on January 11, 2018. Exactly 1 year later, Dakotaz decided to leave TSM of his own will and see what would happen for the rest of 2019.

Dakotaz Controversy

Feud with Ninja

Brett and Tyler “Ninja” Blevins has had backlash at each other while live streaming and on Twitter. It all started on December 19, 2019, with a tweet by Brett talking about how Fortnite is in a “hot garbage” state. Tyler responded saying that he could play another game but gets bored and ‘sleepy’ of other games besides Fortnite.

Tyler made a response while live-streaming stating that Brett should not call the game “garbage” if it doesn’t make him bored or “fall asleep”. Brett’s final response was to let his opinion go through.

Since the beef days later, Brett hated Tyler’s fans sending hate and negativity towards him, and decided to block Tyler on Twitter on December 24, 2019.

fields.title: Bugha
fields.overview: Kyle Giersdorf better known online as Bugha, is an American YouTube gamer who is known for playing Fortnite: Battle Royale competitively. He is mainly known for competing in Fortnite’s World Cup Tournament. He is a member of Sentinels.
fields.body:
Bugha Carrer

Kyle Giersdorf is a young and talented 18 years old American pro gamer. Born on 30 December 2002 in the united states, Pennsylvania, and commonly famous as “Bugha” on social media platforms for his pro gaming skills. Bugha at such a small age made history. When Bugha won the inaugural Fortnite World Cup. In that Bugha overcame 40 million competitors from all around the world and outperformed the final 100 contestants in the Finals live on stage at the Arthur Ashe Stadium. Along which that Bugha also got awarded as the Best Esports Athlete.Along with all these remarkable and outstanding achievements of Bugha in his gaming profession. Bugha also has an astonishing amount of fan following on twitch with 3.9million. Also on youtube with 3.69 million subscribers. With all of this Bugha also got awarded the “best gamer”.

Bugha is one of the most popular names in the online gaming industry. Many teenagers, children, and youngsters spend an enormous amount of their time watching the videos of Bugha. Making Bugha get awarded as the “Best gamer”.Along with his remarkable fan following on social media platforms such as twitch with 3.6million followers and youtube with 3.69 million followers. In addition to all of this Bugha also updates his fans steadily on tweeter, Instagram, and Facebook.

Bugha Success Story

Fortnite is a platform for gamers that has become one of the most successful free-to-play battle royale games in the past three years. As the tournaments continuously happen at Fortnite. An online multiplayer titled game is played by millions of gamers all around the globe. With the players who register themself in it last year, 12.3 million players become a part of that Fortnite tournament. In that particular game 350 million players registered through their gaming videos. Due to all of this Fortnite has become excessively popular among the people. Coming back to Bugha he also got a chance to show his talent in the tournament which made him win the hearts of millions and win $3 million all at the same time.

Bugha Personal Life

Bugha is from a small-town Pennsylvania. Besides his marvelous gaming career, he is in his junior year of high school. From his childhood, Bugha loved playing games which also included playing basketball on the ground which his father and friends. He is also blessed with a caring family and lives life like a normal child who asks each other about their science projects and assignments and makes jokes regarding their teachers. For Bugha Colin is like his best friend for a long time as far as he remembers and tells in his videos. Collin is a person in Bugha life who makes him remember that Bugha is still a normal teenager despite his number of fans and achievements. Collin makes Bugha feel normal with whom Bugha can walk around and eat stuff like organic burgers and drink coke and do all the things done by a teenager.

Bugha Memories

Talking about Bugha memories recently in his upcoming videos he told. Bugha got a passion for playing video games from his father who has played video games his entire life. He also told that Bugha father was the one who introduced him to the game “save the world” but Bugha found his interest in the Battle Royale and he started playing it with his friends and started competing.

Bugha Parents

Bugha mother told that she feels jolly when she hears her son laughing in his room playing video games with the friends he has made. Bugha has a joined family and all these things make him a special kid. As he gets a lot of positivity to move forward in his life and do wonders out of his gaming profession. Bugha family got around to him when he won the Fortnite tournament and brought the trophy home.

fields.title: KingRichard
fields.overview: Richard Nelson better known online as KingRichard, is an American gaming YouTuber and competitve Apex Legends player. Richard mainly found exposure from playing Fortnite.
fields.body:
KingRichard Carrer

Richard Nelson (born: January 11, 1989 [age 31]), better known online as KingRichard, is an American gaming YouTuber and competitve Apex Legends player.

Richard mainly found exposure from playing Fortnite and is widely known for being stream sniped by a user known as King Richards Loot.

On April 2, 2019, Richard made a response on his Twitch livestream.

In 2014, King Richard started off making streams and videos in 2014 as an ESO (Elder Scrolls Online) YouTuber and streamer. He managed to get over 10,000 subscribers on YouTube. Richard then additionally made Overwatch content in 2016.

Richard has been exposed for scamming a Graphic Artist named G4K. Richard refused to pay their part of a deal that produced numerous custom elements for him to use. G4K took his team’s predicament to look for some form of recompense after Richard discontinued communication with G4K.

Richard Nelson is known online as King Richard, is an American gaming YouTuber and competitive Apex Legends player. Richard mainly found exposure from playing Fortnite and is widely known for being stream sniped by a user known as King Richards Loot. King Richards’ most popular videos are on about King Richards Loot stream sniping him just to give out extra weapons and materials towards Richard himself. He is also known for playing with multiple other streamers known as Tfue, Ninja, CDNThe3rd, and Dakotaz. He is 31 years old and was born on January 11, 1989

KingRichard History

King Richard started off making streams and videos in 2014 as an ESO (Elder Scrolls Online) YouTuber and streamer. He managed to get over 10,000 subscribers on YouTube. Richard then additionally made Overwatch content in 2016. Richard was able to surpass 16,000 subscribers and 2 million video views before playing Fortnite. Richard made his debut in Fortnite with high kill games, and later, King Richards Loot came in to play.

KingRichard Controversy

Scamming a Graphic Artist

Richard has been exposed for scamming a Graphic Artist named G4K. Richard refused to pay their part of a deal that produced numerous custom elements for him to use. G4K took his team’s predicament to look for some form of recompense after Richard discontinued communication with G4K.

G4K’s work with Richard was set as a “full rebrand”, planned by Richard himself, but G4K alleges that Richard did not provide any further payment for any of the work upon its’ completion. He also alleges that Richard actually used the assets on stream for over a week since the controversy arose.

KingRichard Response

On April 2, 2019, Richard made a response on his Twitch livestream.

“I reached out to G4K, I sent him a DM on Twitter,” Richard said. “But that’s kind of fucked up to straight up say ‘yeah, he’s a scammer….’ These fuckers didn’t do half the shit they were supposed to do. It took them five months to get to this point… I would never scam anybody, I am not that type of person.” Richard said that he and his manager have been getting harassed because of the deal that they say is fabricated. “If this particular artist wants to come up with an apology and tell the truth about their side of the story, and let people know the full side of it and that I’m not a fuckin scammer then we can talk,” Richard said.

Richard, after his lengthy discussion, took a break before coming back to practice for an upcoming Apex Legends Twitch Rivals tournament. It appears he spoke to G4K during that break and the two sides agreed to work on the matter privately and won’t be public on the situation anymore.

fields.title: starxo
fields.overview: Starxo is a competitive Valorant player who currently plays for the Team Acend. He is of Polish nationality and is of 21 years of age. His real name is Patryk Kopczunski and he was born on 28 August 2001. Starxo's main agents are Sage, Astra and sometimes Viper. He usually plays the support/smoker role for his roster.
fields.body:
Starxo Carrer

Starxo started grinding Valorant ever since the game came out. Eventually, his performance in pubs was noticed by scouts and he made his debut as a professional player. He played for the Team 'Those Guys' and then joined Entropiq. After his rise on the leaderboards, he was picked up by Raise Your Edge Gaming. Although his time in RYEG was short and unsuccessful lasting only 2 months. 

He eventually joined Acend and its roster on 10 March 2021. Acend has since gone on to win multiple LAN events with starxo. They won the Valorant Champions 2021 against Gambit in a BO5. Starxo and the team won $350,000 as prize money after lifting the trophy. Patryk was the star performer of the Grand Final with the most amount of kills despite playing support agents. He had 83 kills and 32 assists across all five maps. 

The game was decided after the tie-breaker on Split went in the favour of Acend. This series cemented the position of starxo as one of Acend's key components. Starxo's total earnings are estimated to be around $102,000 from cash prizes and prize earnings.

fields.title: SypherPK

SypherPK Carrer

He is well known for his Educational Fortnite Gameplay (Tips and Tricks). He is a part of Team Luminosity[2]. Sypher has been well known for his high kill gameplays in Fortnite along with collaborations with other big YouTubers / Twitch Streamers.

Ali Hassan better known online as SypherPK is a professional Fortnite player on YouTube and Twitch. He is well known for his Educational Fortnite Gameplay (Tips and Tricks). fields.title: Boaster
fields.overview: Boaster is a competitive Valorant player and the in-game leader for Team Fnatic. He was previously a professional Counter-Strike: Global Offensive player. His real name is Jake Howlett and he is of British nationality. Jake was born on May 25, 1995 and is of 26 years of age. He was also a League Of Legends player with Team Excel before beginning his FPS journey with Counter Strike. His main agents are Breach, Sova and Astra. He usually plays the initiator or smoke role for his team.
fields.body:
Boaster Carrier

As a young teenager Boaster used to work in a musical theatre. These talents helped him become a vibrant personality in the streaming community. Boaster's twitch streams are often filled with him playing the ukulele, singing, and performing. His other interests include watching anime and reading manga. Jake started his esports career with Counter Strike in 2014 and retired midway through 2019 after failing to have an impact on the professional scene. 

He later tried his luck in MOBA games like League Of Legends. Boaster climbed ranks and was Diamond after six months of playing LOL. He later joined Excel as a substitute but found difficulty adapting to the game. This was around the time Valorant came out and Jake switched to FPS again. He alongside other aspiring pro-players formed a team and called it 'SUMN FC'. This team won numerous tournaments such as Lava Series and Epic Lan. 

The biggest achievement of this SUMN FC roster came in June of 2021. Boaster and team managed to finish with a second spot finish in the Valorant Masters Reykjavik in Iceland. His post-game interviews and his luring personality gained traction in the Valorant community. Soon the entire SUMN FC team was signed by Fnatic and Boaster became the in-game leader. 

Jake is estimated to earn around $2,300 a month from his Twitch subscription services. Apart from this he earns income from his salary, sponsorships, tournament winnings and donations. His total net worth is assumed to be around $100,000.

fields.title: Elige
fields.overview: EliGe played Counter Strike 1.6 for passing time in his young age, but he always had his focus on StarCraft II early on. The young boy quickly made his mark in the game, with getting signed by Liquid replacing Keith ‘NAF’ Markovic.
fields.body:
Elige Career

EliGe started to come to his being in 2017, where following the departure of s1mple, Liquid entrusted him with more and more responsibilities. He took upon them as Achilles once took upon Troy, playing a spotless year with zero negative showings at any event and becoming the 12th best player of the A.D. year 2017. He aided Liquid to secure second place rankings at ESG 1 NY and ESG Tour Mykonos.

In 2018 his charge continued as steadily as Prometheus’ against gods, with the American rifler becoming once again one of the top 20 players of the year. This year Liquid won their first tournaments (CS Summit II & SuperNova Malta CS: GO) and showed up at the finals of ESL Pro League Season VII and Season VIII finales, ESL NY and IEM Chicago.

The liquid went out to Poland to play IEM Katowice, where they were routed and confined to the 6th place. But EliGe maintained his dignity in this rout as Hector did in that of Troy, earning his first EVP mention of the year with a 1.35 impact rating, 1.18 rating, and 87.5 ADR in the 9 maps that the team played in.

EliGe then adopted a constitution colder than a vampire’s demeanor and went on a rampage. In ESL Pro League Season XI, he got a 1.27 rating, 1.38 impact rating, and 90.5 ADR across sixteen maps. This led to him winning the only MVP award of that year.
His performances were as consistent as Manoel De Oliviera’s filmography, but Liquid could not win anything at ESL I and DreamHack Masters Spring 2020. Despite not winning a darn tooting, EliGe was again bestowed with 2 more EVPs for his brilliant gaming. Liquid’s luck started improving a dime when at ESL 1 Cologne North America they secured the second rank. EliGe, needless to say, was playing like his usual excellent-self and added yet another EVP to his tally (now four).

Achievements:

In IEM NY North America, Liquid finished fifth. This low performance found no concurrence in that of EliGe’s play, where he managed to get a 98.6 ADR ad 1.47 impact rating in sixteen maps, with the rating of 1.36 which made him worthy of yet another EVP.

In 2020, the year of the deadly Tom Hanks Disease, EliGe was one of the most dangerous players on the server, attaining the 4th highest damage output (84.2 ADR), ranking seventh in kills per round as well as 12th in assists per round. He also had the fourth-highest impact rating, that of 1.28, which seems to call for him the same attribution that Milton once made for Cromwell ‘If these be the times, this be the man’.

fields.title: Hamlinz
fields.overview: Darryle Hamlin better known online as Hamlinz, is an American YouTuber and Twitch streamer who is best known for playing Fortnite. Hamlinz is a member of TSM (Team SoloMid).
fields.body:
Hamlinz Carrer

Top Fortnite player Myth invited Hamlinz to the team and Hamlinz has since regularly participated in tournament matches with his teammates. Hamlinz and Daequan most recently won second place in the Friday Fortnite competition and Hamlinz has also had several victories partnered with Myth.

His addition to TSM has only further spurred his popularity and increased his fanbase. TSM recently purchased a home in Beverly Hills, in which each of the team members has permanently moved. Living in the TSM house has allowed other team members to make quick appearances during his streams, creating crossovers for fans of each player.

Hamlin grew up in Virginia with his parents and mentions that he got into gaming around that time. He was eight years old when his parents introduced him to it. His first gaming console was Super Nintendo.

Hamlinz played RuneScape for many years, ultimately using it as the start of his gaming career. Hamlinz treats his gaming very seriously and regularly streams upwards of 40 hours of content a week.

Hamlinz is about 5ft 5in tall and he’s a Gemini. He currently resides at the TSM Gaming House in California. His net worth is estimated at $900 thousand. He earns from Twitch subscribers, donations, YouTube, and tournament winnings.

Darryle Hamlin better known online as Hamlinz (or Hamz), is an American YouTuber and Twitch streamer who is best known for playing Fortnite. Hamlinz is a member of TSM (Team SoloMid), a professional eSports group. Darryle is commonly known for being “sus” and reacting to YouTube videos. He is 25 years old and was born on May 23, 1995.

Hamlinz History

Even though he only has one video before Fortnite, which is Runescape, Hamlinz only had 20 subscribers and didn’t get at least 1 view a day before doing Fortnite. His growth on YouTube because of Fortnite is late, but thanks to it, he is now getting rapid success and gains nearly 10,000 subscribers every day thanks to Fortnite and also TSM collabs. He is also in the TSM house with Myth and Daequan Loco.

Hamlinz Hiatuses

First Hiatus

Darryle was on a hiatus for unknown reasons, but people assume that he is diagnosed with Cancer, from a deleted tweet.[5] However, on October 19, 2019, Darryle made an announcement stating that he took a hiatus due to his Grandmother being diagnosed with cancer, and decided to take a hiatus to take some time to mentally reset and visit his grandmother. He is scheduled to return on October 20.

Hamlinz Hacked

During Darryle’s hiatus, his Twitter was hacked by Chuckling Squad

Second Hiatus

Since December 30, 2019, Darryle has stopped live streaming and uploading again. He announced on January 15, 2020, that he was speaking with HealthyGamerGG to help him cope with the loss of his Grandfather...

fields.title: Derke
fields.overview: Derke is a professional Valorant player who plays for the Valorant team Fnatic. His real name is Nikita Sirmitev and he was previously a pro-Counter Strike player before retiring and switching to Valorant. Nikita is Russian and of Finnish descent. He is 19 years of age and was born on February 6, 2003.
fields.body:
Derke Carrer

Derke was previously known as Derkeps on Counter-Strike. He was a talented awper and destined to be the next big star. However, with the rise of Valorant, he made the switch and transitioned perfectly, wielding the operator. His main agents are Jett and Raze. Before joining Fnatic Derke was a player for Team CrowCrowd. He joined Fnatic along with Magnum when the duo was signed as replacements for two of Fnatic's current players.

He was part of the Fnatic squad that reached the finals of the VCT Masters - Reykjavík. They ended second place to an invincible Sentinel squad. Derke is known to be one of the most feared Jett players in the EU region. His style of awning is adapted from Counter-Strike and other traditional FPS games. Derke is estimated to have earned around $50,000 in prize earnings from his tournament winnings.

fields.title: Mongraal
fields.overview: Kyle Jackson better known online as Mongraal, is an English eSports player who mainly plays the game Fortnite. At 13 years old, he had found success, and was featured on BBC News.
fields.body:
Mongraal Carrer

At 13 years old, he had found success and was featured on BBC News. Kyle was a player for Team Secret (joined in April 2018) but decided to leave the clan on July 7, 2019, to join FaZe Clan.

Summer Skirmish is a Weekly tournament hosted by Fortnite themselves which comes in on Multiple days. Kyle was not allowed to join due to him being too young, as Kyle did mention that he is one of the top players when it came to other tournaments. Kyle also mentioned that he cannot control his age which is unfair as he is the youngest competitive player in the world.

Ever since the release of Fortnite’s Creative, multiple content creators on YouTube made maps for the community to use for practice or challenges.

He also had gained around 200% of exposure on his social media, going from 44,000 YouTube subscribers to 159,000 subscribers that day.

Kyle Jackson better known online as Mongraal is an English eSports teen who mainly plays the game Fortnite. He is known for his plays and aggressiveness in the game. People look him up due to him playing very well at a young age. At 13 years old, he had found success and was featured on BBC News. Kyle was a player for Team Secret (joined in April 2018) but decided to leave the clan on July 7, 2019, to join FaZe Clan. He is 15 years old and was born on August 13, 2004.

Mongraal Awards and Achievements

Overall Ranking: At this time, Mongraal is ranked #180 in highest overall earnings, and #2 in highest earnings for players from the United Kingdom.

Prize Money Earned Under 18 Years of Age: Mongraal is presently under the age of 18. All prize money won will count towards this category until August 13, 2022.

Largest Prize from a Single Tournament: Out of the 33 tournaments awarding cash prizes that Mongraal had competed in, the largest amount was $225,000.00 from Fortnite World Cup Finals 2019 – Duo on July 27, 2019. He placed 6th, making up 37.29% of his total prize money won.

$100,000 Milestone: Mongraal obtained $100,000 in total prize money earned on July 27, 2019, with a $225,000.00 cash prize from his 6th place finish at Fortnite World Cup Finals 2019 – Duo. Prize money from 18 tournaments got him to that point.

Mongraal Controversy

Summer Skirmish

Summer Skirmish is a Weekly tournament hosted by Fortnite themselves which comes in on Multiple days. Kyle was not allowed to join due to him being too young[2], as Kyle did mention that he is one of the top players when it came to other tournaments. Kyle also mentioned that he cannot control his age which is unfair as he is the youngest competitive player in the world.

BBC News Interview

In April 2018, Kyle was interviewed by the company ‘BBC’ (British Broadcasting Corporation) as he was the #1 British Fortnite Player and Youngest Competitive Fortnite player. Kyle had mentioned that he had played games his whole life and started playing more professionally at the age of 9 when he was playing Halo and Call of Duty. There were also questions about Kyle’s school work. Kyle responded by saying that he has time to study and is doing well in all subjects in school, and his parents don’t have any worry about him playing a lot.

Edit Course

Ever since the release of Fortnite’s Creative, multiple content creators on YouTube made maps for the community to use for practice or challenges. Kyle created his building/editing course. The server was also used for a $500 giveaway to the person who can finish Kyle’s edit course the fastest.

Currently, the person who has finished Kyle’s edit course the fastest is Pxlarized with a time of 2 minutes and 26 seconds.

fields.title: Mitr0
fields.overview: Mitr0 or Dmitri van de Vrie is a professional Fortnite player for Team Liquid who has been making a name for himself in various tournaments against FNCS pros. He started his career in June 2018 when he sided with Mongraal to compete in numerous events, including the Fortnite World Cup Duo Championship.
fields.body:
Mitr0 Career

Fortnite is one of the most popular Esports titles today alongside Valorant and other shooters. This battle royale/sandbox game was released in 2017. It boasts a huge community and has over 4.8 million active players. Mitr0 is one of the famous names in the Fortnite community, constantly outperforming other professionals and winning tournaments. He is a competitive Fortnite player representing Team Liquid.

His first-ever major accomplishment on the professional stage was during the Fortnite Summer Skirmish in Europe. Mitr0 managed to finish 1st twice during the 3rd and 5th week. He also placed 1st during the 2nd and 3rd week of the Fortnite Fall Skirmish.

Since then, Mitr0 has performed exceptionally well in all of the tournaments he has participated in and has received tons of support from the Fortnite community. This includes some tournaments such as Winter Royale, Fortnite World Cup Duos, FNCS Season 4, and more.

Mitr0 also has a Twitch channel with over 800,000 followers, where he regularly streams Fortnite. He also uploads highlights of his Fortnite streams on YouTube where he has 736,000+ subscribers.

Net Worth

Mitr0’s earnings are predominantly cash prizes from the Fortnite tournaments he has participated in. Before MitrO even turned 18, he was awarded over $733,774 in cash prizes from 71 different tournaments. More than 90% of his total prize money/income was earned before June 6, 2020. Mitr0 stands at #2 in highest earnings from an esports player from the Netherlands. The biggest prize pool that Mitr0 has secured for himself was $225,000 from Fortnite World Cup Finals 2019 – Duo on July 27, 2019. His 6th place finish in the tournament still accounts for a majority of his net worth, up to 28% of his total prize money won.

Mitr0’s YouTube channel consistently gets more than 1.56 million views each month which amounts to 52,000 views each day. Since YouTube channels earn between $3 to $7 per a thousand views depending on the region, it’s fair to assume that MitrO earns approximately around $7,000 every month or $84,000 yearly.

Mitr0 also has a popular Twitch channel which has garnered over 800,000 followers. He has a total of 9 million views and 4,000 average viewers. With Twitch channels earning between $3 to $10 per one thousand views, Mitr0 could be estimated to earn around $20 to $30 every stream.

Mitr0 is not very active on Twitch and hence his Twitch channel doesn’t have many followers and viewers as compared to other professional players. Factoring in his social media influence and his earnings on Twitch, YouTube, and sponsorships, MitrO’s estimated net worth would be around $800,000 to $900,000.

Mitr0 reached the $100,000 milestone when he obtained $100,000 in prize money earned on August 25, 2018. He achieved this feat with a $9,975 cash prize from his 4th place finish at Fortnite Summer Skirmish Series – Week 7 EU (Day 2). It took him cash prizes from 6 tournaments to reach this milestone Recently in the past few months Mitr0 has won $2,000 in cash prizes from a single tournament.

Controversies

Underpaid by Team Atlantis

On September 15, 2019, a hashtag by the signs of ‘#FreeMitrO’ started going viral on Twitter, among the Fortnite Competitive Community. It was meant to highlight Dmitri a young Fortnite player being underpaid by his organization, Team Atlantis. This has happened to other professionals as well, including some big names like ‘Edgey’, a member of FlyQuest.

Team Atlantis took 2/3rds of the winnings from Dmitri. Having granted only $30,000 out of the $90,000 MitrO earned from the Trios Championship Series. Some Atlantis players have also expressed their concern claiming to have lost around 70% of their income from the Fortnite World Cup 2019.

Mitr0 joined Atlantis as an amateur before his success as a player and a streamer, having a very small community. However, after his spectacular performances, he surpassed the organization in terms of popularity and was unhappy with his contract. This resulted in him wanting to leave Atlantis back in Jan 2019. MitrO looked for an organization that was capable of handling a player of his caliber and fulfilling his demands. MitrO left Team Atlantis for Team Liquid on 27 September 2019.

fields.title: Daequan
fields.overview: Daequan Loco is an American YouTuber, Twitch Streamer, and a Professional Fortnite player. Daequan is known for popularizing the ‘Double Pump’, winning Fortnite’s early invitationals, and for his comedic humor.
fields.body:
Daequan Carrer

He started his Daequan Loco channel just for Fortnite content. He is a member of Team SoloMid (TSM). As of June 4, 2019, Daequan is on a hiatus due to health problems.

On March 9, 2018, Daequan had once set a World Record for most eliminations in a Fortnite Game. He got 39 eliminations in a game by himself in a Team of 20 matches.

On September 19, 2019, Daequan made a video explaining what had been going on during his latest times. He claims that Fortnite was not as enjoyable as it used to be (and also says he will no longer play competitively), his girlfriend (Exie) dealing with health problems, stress, and talking about his past health issues.

Daequan Loco Net Worth – $4 Million. Daequan Loco is a popular Twitch streamer from Florida, United States who is also known as TSM_Daequan. He has an estimated net worth of $4 million.

Daequan Loco is an American YouTuber, Twitch Streamer, and a Professional Fortnite player who currently resides in Los Angeles, California. Daequan is known for popularizing the ‘Double Pump’, winning Fortnite’s early invitationals, and for his comedic humor. He started his Daequan Loco channel just for Fortnite content. He is a member of Team SoloMid (TSM). As of June 4, 2019, Daequan is on a hiatus due to health problems. He is 26 years old and was born on May 12, 1994.

Daequan Awards and Achievements

He is the Finalist in TWITCH STREAMER OF THE YEAR

Known above all for his Fortnite content, Daequan Loco is one of the founders of the TSM team and top streamers for his elite-level skill across a variety of first-person shooter games. He’s a leading eSports player with a growing fanbase on Twitch, and set a world record for the most kills in a Fortnite game, netting 38 by himself in a team match. For Fortnite fanatics, his channel is a must-visit for ridiculous Fortnite streams and insightful commentary, as his 3M+ Twitch followers already know and tune in regularly to enjoy.

On March 9, 2018, Daequan had once set a World Record for most eliminations in a Fortnite Game. He got 39 eliminations in a game by himself in a Team of 20 matches. However, on April 30, 2018, a YouTuber known as Teeqzy makes the new world record of 45 eliminations, surpassing Daequan by 6. Daequan’s duo partner, Hamlin, was eliminated 5 minutes after the start of the match. Hamlinz got 4 eliminations in that game with Daequan having 39, which sums 43 eliminations. That total had once become the second most eliminations from a duo team. Currently, Daequan’s video formerly making a world record is the most popular video with over 19 million views.

On May 10, 2018, Daequan moved to Los Angeles when he and his TSM team successfully created their own house with Myth and Hamlinz.

Daequan Joining TSM

Daequan became a part of TSM in February 2018 signing on to be a part of TSM’s competitive Fortnite squad. He has had a storied gaming history, having played numerous games at a competitive level including but not limited to Destiny 1 PvP, Black Desert Online, GunZ, Wildstar, and Smite. He logged an insubstantial amount of time on H1Z1 before discovering Fortnite, which is ostensibly his first Battle Royale game, where he is well known for having the most invitational wins in North America and significantly influencing the meta through his gameplay.

“I feel blessed that TSM is an organization that I could join. It’s important to me that Reginald was also an eSports player so he can understand what it’s like for us and relate. Being a part of this organization is beyond words and I am grateful to every one of you that has been a part of it and I can’t wait to see what the future holds for us. We have an amazing team with genuine personalities and I hope to build lasting relationships between all of us and that we are able to grow not only in our businesses and channels but as people as well and go on to do great things in the future. I do not doubt in my mind that we won’t be 100% successful in all that we encounter!” ~ Daequan

Daequan Hiatus

On May 30, 2019, Daequan stated on Twitter that he was having stomach problems. On June 3, Daequan started mentioning that he had been facing multiple problems and is enduring pain “24/7”. Daequan also mentions his early basketball life, where he claims he never stretched. On June 19, Daequan stated that he is slowly starting to feel better. On June 29, Daequan shared that his spine was misaligned. On July 4, Daequan stated that he should be able to make a return this month (July). He made a return on August 9, 2019.

Daequan Changes

On September 19, 2019, Daequan made a video explaining what had been going on during his latest times. He claims that Fortnite was not as enjoyable as it used to be (and also says he will no longer play competitively), his girlfriend (Exie) dealing with health problems, stress, and talking about his past health issues.

Daequan Trivia

Daequan won the first-ever Fortnite Invitational (Custom Matchmaking game) back in December 2017. He was widely considered the best Fortnite player and started his rise to popularity at first.

Daequan is also a 5-time invitational winner since the early era of Fortnite: Battle Royale.
Daequan started the infamous ‘W-Key’, which is commonly said by other Fortnite streamers.

fields.title: Ghost Aydan
fields.overview: Aydan Conrad formerly known as Ghost Aydan, is an American competitive eSports gamer. Aydan first found major success after defeating NICKMERCS in Fortnite’s Summer Skirmish 4 times with Aydan winning every encounter against Nick.
fields.body:
Ghost Aydan Career

Aydan Conrad better known online as Ghost Aydan or simply Aydan is an American competitive eSports gamer. Aydan first found major success after defeating NICKMERCS in Fortnite’s Summer Skirmish

Both NICKMERCS and Aydan were qualified for Fortnite’s first tournament, the Summer Skirmish. The 2 facing off were the most talked about due to both the players being on Controller. Aydan once claimed he only had 100 viewers on average before his success from the Summer Skirmish, and now tops off 10,000 viewers on average. During the mid-games and end-games of the tournament, Aydan loves to play aggressively in the game.

The 2 have encountered each other multiple times but have yet to kill each other yet. Nick and Aydan were inside a hotel in Tilted Towers, and Nick was standing still to hear Aydan. They both counter each other, Nick taking away half of Aydan’s health, but building away while Nick was shooting.

Aydan Conrad better known online as Ghost Aydan or simply Aydan is an American competitive eSports gamer. Aydan first found major success after defeating NICKMERCS in Fortnite’s Summer Skirmish 4 times with Aydan winning every encounter against NICKMERCS. He is 21 years old and was born May 25, 1999

Aydan became a member of Ghost Gaming on August 3, 2018, which gave Aydan minor growth, and helped him gain extra viewers before the Summer Skirmish. Aydan is widely known for his aggressive gameplays and high kill risky gameplays, which are frequently uploaded to the Ghost Aydan YouTube channel.

Both NICKMERCS and Aydan were qualified for Fortnite’s first tournament, the Summer Skirmish. The 2 facing off were the most talked about due to both the players being on Controller. Aydan once claimed he only had 100 viewers on average before his success from the Summer Skirmish, and now tops off 10,000 viewers on average. During the mid-games and end-games of the tournament, Aydan loves to play aggressively in the game.

Encounter #1

The first encounter did not last long. Nick was inside a building (which people call ‘Trump Tower’) at a location named Tilted Towers. Aydan was shooting at Nick from the window outside of the tower and quickly killed Nick. After the kill, Aydan decided to dance on Nick to impress the viewers.

Encounter #2

The second encounter took a long. The 2 have encountered each other multiple times but have yet to kill each other yet. Nick and Aydan were inside a hotel in Tilted Towers, and Nick was standing still to hear Aydan. They both counter each other, Nick taking away half of Aydan’s health, but building away while Nick was shooting.

But just shortly after, they both go up a few floors to catch up, with Aydan getting a shotgun shot at Nick. Nick runs outside and hits Aydan with a shotgun shot. Aydan was 2 health remaining but luckily had healed from the chest. Nick remained at 76 health. Nick disengages to find heals for himself.

They both find each other at “Trump Tower” inside Tilted Towers. Aydan decided to push Nick inside. And the health advantage Aydan had saved him against Nickmercs, eliminating him. Aydan was down to 20 health but managed to survive the second encounter between each other.

Encounter #3

The third encounter started at the newly constructed area of Tilted Towers. Nick and Aydan did not hit each other yet but then engages again in “Trump Tower”. Aydan does get hit 2 times by a third party but did not take much effect. Nick surprised attack Aydan alongside Aydan fighting back, but Nick quickly disengages. Aydan then threw a stinkbomb to lower Nick’s health.

20 seconds later, Nick gets a shotgun shot towards Aydan, but Aydan throws a second stink bomb. Aydan does come across a third-party Misfits Jiren, but Aydan quickly eliminates him.

Inside the same area of “Trump Tower”, they both engage again with Aydan throwing his last stink bomb at Nick, though Aydan does tag himself a few times. And 1 floor below their impact area, Nick and Aydan fight it out. Nick accidentally switches to his heals, and Aydan takes the game again. To impress the viewers, Aydan uses the ‘Slow Clap’ emote right after killing Nick.

Encounter #4

The fourth encounter was also short. They both were in “Trump Tower” yet again. Aydan places a trap to prevent Nick from following him but moved to another path. Nick does hit Aydan with a shotgun. Aydan then throws a C4 remote explosive, successfully hitting Nick, and finishes Nick with the Submachine Gun as Nick was looking to push Aydan.

Fall Skirmish – Duo Partners

Fortnite’s second tournament Fall Skirmish occurred and was duo mode only. Nick and Aydan decided to become duo partners to attempt to play aggressively against other duo teams. They were successfully able to pop off and in 2 games, they both had 10 eliminations combined. They both also impressed the live viewers in almost the entire Fall Skirmish finals. Unfortunately, they did not win a game...

Ghost Aydan Controversy

Smurfing in Arena

Throughout a portion of September in 2019, Aydan has been smurfing in Fortnite (meaning he is on an alternative account to play in a competitive mode, with the low-rank players) to get a record inside of it, or for content. While he did make a world record of getting 42 eliminations before being surpassed by Gorb, Aydan put a reaction out of it, which sparked more hatred.

Eventually, Aydan was banned for a day due to exploitation.

fields.title: BONECOLD
fields.overview: Bonecold is a Finnish player whose real name is Santeri Sassi. He currently plays for the team Acend. Santeri previously played for Teams such as hREDS and Raise Your Edge Gaming. He ended up joining Acend on 10th October 2021. Bonecold has earnings from different cash cups and tournament winnings which total about $100,000.

BONECOLD Carrer

He is currently 23 years of age and has represented 3 teams in competitive Valorant. His biggest achievements include winning the Valorant Champions 2021 against Gambit which had a cash prize of $350,000. Bonecold played his favorite agents in the BO5 finals which included Sova, Breach, and Omen. He had a great showing in the final with 166 ACS and a total of 63 kills across all 5 maps. Bonecold had the highest headshot percentage in the finals converting 39% of his kills with headshots.

The match went the distance and both the teams ended up playing all 5 maps. Eventually, Acend bagged the victory in the final decider map Split where Bonecold was playing Omen. His other achievements also include winning the VCT 2021: Europe Stage 1 Masters 3:2 against Heretics which had a prize of $60,000.

fields.title: woxic
fields.overview: When Dark Passage was hitting the number one rank in a group that included Ukraine, TYLOO, and Selfless, it was Woxic who was one of the main protagonists engineering this charge. His rise to fame has been anything but a straight line: his first match was when he was 16 years old, and his average was a dismal 0.72. But playing alongside players such as TaZ, Shox and Snax lit the furnace of ambition in this 16-year-old boy which was to go a long way.
fields.body:
woxic Career

His breakthrough would come years later, when having placed second at WESG Turkey, Dark Passages was qualified to attend the Africa & Middle Regional Finals, in Dubai, where Woxic garnered an average of 1.26 as the team finished 3rd.

But shortly after the event, things started deteriorating for Dark Passage. The contract of all the players expired, and star player Bugra ‘Calyx’ Arkin left the team for Space Soldiers. But Woxic did not let these developments affect him, using this time to improve his English-speaking skills. He started to stream his games online and soon got an offer from HellRaisers.

It was up then for Woxic, who aided HellRaisers to win the FCDB Cup, with a rating of 1.53, 83.8 percentage KAST, and 0.57 AWP. He then played a pivotal role in HellRaisers winning another LAN title at Kyiv and also aided to win the CIS Minor leading to FACEIT Major. He dropped in the final a 40-bomb in the fight against Spirit.

He then played a pivotal role in HellRaisers winning another LAN title at Kyiv and also aided to win the CIS Minor leading to FACEIT Major. He dropped in the final a 40-bomb in the fight against Spirit.

But soon things started falling apart for HellRaisers since they were heavily dependent on just two players: Woxic and ISSAA. They struggled at IEM Katowice where they lost 1-3. Seeing that the tides were flowing volatile for HellRaisers, and joined the Finnish group MOUZ. He helped the team to defeat AVANGAR, Winding, and Valiance at the DreamHack Open Tours, and he garnered a rating of 1.25, damage difference per round of 14.3, and DPR of 0.60.

Achievements:

Woxic entered the EVP list for the first time in the year 2019, where he secured team-leading performances against Evil Geniuses (1.31), OpTic (1.51), and Grayhound (1.63). He followed that up with another brilliant performance in the team’s group stage exist at Star Series i-League with a rating of 1.22, posting a KDD of 45 plus and an impact of 1.26.

fields.title: Tfue
fields.overview: Turner Ellis Tenney better known online as Tfue is an American eSports player from Florida. He has gained most of his success playing Fortnite.
fields.body:
Tfue Carrer

Turner Ellis Tenney (born on January 2, 1998) professionally known by his online alias Tfue is an American streamer. He is an esports player playing Fortnite. He has gained his success by playing Fortnite but currently, he streams Call of Duty: Modern Warfare on Twitch.

Turner is a member of JOOGSQUAD and he had done a lot of collaborative videos on the channel containing scooters, stunts, skateboarding, and surfing. After that, he did a lot of cliff and bridge jumping. After that Turner started his own YouTube channel and Twitch channel as a Destiny YouTuber and Call of Duty.

In 2016, he moved on to H1Z1 and then started playing PUBG

Tfue’s net worth is estimated to be in the region of $4-6 million (£3.25-4.88 million). This takes into account his revenue from Twitch through subscribers and donations, YouTube revenue, sponsors, and earnings from competitive Fortnite tournaments.

Turner Ellis Tenney is better known by his online alias Tfue, is an American streamer and esports player, best known for playing Fortnite. He is 22 years old and was born on January 2, 1998.

He is regarded as one of the best players on Fortnite and has won many tournaments including most recently the SuperGames Charity Tournament, in which two streamers teamed up with two professional athletes to compete as a four-man squad against 19 other squads.

Tfue Awards and Achievements

At present, Tfue is ranked #176 in highest overall earnings, and #24 in highest earnings for players from the United States.

Largest Prize from a Single Tournament: Out of the 43 tournaments awarding cash prizes that Tfue had competed in, the largest amount was $255,000.00 from Fortnite Fall Skirmish Series – Week 6 – Grand Finals on October 28, 2018. He placed 1st, making up 41.74% of his total prize money won.

$100,000 Milestone: Tfue overtook the $100,000 milestone on August 17, 2018, winning $6,150.00 and placing 2nd at Fortnite Summer Skirmish Series – Week 6 NA (Day 1). Prize money from 15 tournaments got him to that point.

Recent Earnings: Tfue has been awarded $1,500.00 in cash prizes from a single tournament within the last 90 days, all of which came in the last month.

Tfue Career

Tfue transitioned to Fortnite Battle Royale as it was quickly exploding in popularity. Tenney later joined FaZe Clan, a professional esports organization, on April 30, 2018.

Tfue Personal life

Tenney is from Indian Rocks Beach, Florida. He went to middle school for a week but thought that “[…] it sucked [there] […]” which is why “[…] he never really went to school […]” after that and was homeschooled. In 2019, he moved to New Jersey with his duo partner Cloakzy.

Tfue Controversies

In May 2018, Tenney was banned from Twitch for 30 days after saying an alleged racial slur. Twitch reversed the ban after reviewing the word wasn’t used racially.

On July 2, 2018, Tenney received a permanent account ban on his Epic Games accounts because he was selling and buying Epic Games accounts, which is prohibited by Epic Games’ terms and conditions.[8] A week later, Tenney was banned from Twitch again, this time for 14 days, for unknown reasons.

On May 20, 2019, Tenney filed a lawsuit against FaZe Clan, claiming they “pressured Tenney to live in one of its homes in Los Angeles, pressured him to underage drinking and illegal gambling. FaZe also continuously pressured and encouraged him to engage in dangerous stunts.” Tenney also claimed, that “he only got 20% from any branded videos that are published on Twitch, YouTube or social media and half of his revenue from touring and appearances.” FaZe Clan responded on Twitter, saying they didn’t take any money from his tournament winnings, Twitch and YouTube revenue and his social media. They also said that they “took $60,000 from his branded videos” and offered Tenney “an improved contract multiple times, with 100% of the money going to Tenney, but he rejected or ignored all of them.”

On August 1, 2019, FaZe Clan filed a federal lawsuit in New York suing Tenney, claiming Tenney violated his contract by disparaging the company and trying to form a rival esports organization. The organization also claims that Tenney directly leaked confidential information about his contract to media publications, violating their terms.

On September 2, 2019, Tenney again said a racial slur while streaming, but Twitch did not ban him.

On April 25, 2020, Tenney competed in a rock, paper, scissors charity tournament hosted by Jimmy “MrBeast” Donaldson. During Tenney’s stream of the tournament, he accidentally revealed MrBeast’s phone number and code for the tournament contestants. The stream had to be taken down momentarily before return which Tenney quickly lost. Tenney apologized but received criticism from many people including Tyler “Ninja” Blevins. Tenney responded by calling Ninja a “pussy” during a rant on stream.

fields.title: Nexa
fields.overview: Nemanja “nexa” Isaković is a Serbian professional Counter-Strike: Global Offensive player who plays for G2 Esports as the in-game leader and a rifler.
fields.body:
Nexa Career

Nemanja “nexa” Isaković is a Serbian professional Counter-Strike: Global Offensive player who plays for G2 Esports as the in-game leader and a rifler.

Nexa began carving his trail in the Balkan Counter-Strike scene in 2010, playing in a series of tournaments held across Bosnia and Serbia. In the following two years, he had the chance to witness first-hand the chasm between the world’s finest and the best that his region could offer when he attended Adepto BH Open 2011, in Sarajevo, and DreamHack Bucharest 2012 as part of eu4ia and iNation. In both tournaments, Nexa’s teams could not make it past the quarter-finals following blowout defeats to two different iterations of Fnatic.

With CS: GO taking over and bringing the 1.6 and Source communities together, Nexa made the switch and continued to play with iNation, who added two more experienced players in Janko “⁠YNk⁠” Paunović and Nemanja “⁠k1Ng0r⁠” Bošković. The team failed to make the playoffs at Mad Catz Vienna and DreamHack Bucharest, hitting a brick wall every time they faced tougher opposition, such as VeryGames and LDLC, but their breakthrough came later in 2013, at StarSeries VIII, where they came in as a late replacement for Clan-Mystik.

Rise To Fame

The Serbian team, who had reached an agreement with GamePub just days before the event, surpassed all expectations as they finished in third place, beating Astana Dragons and playing close series against AGAiN and Natus Vincere, with NiKo showing that he could be a force in the future as he put up a team-high 1.11 rating. The Serbian prodigy was starting to make a name for himself, but he ended up taking a break from the game in 2014 after internal issues and some disappointing results had brought his team to an end.

Nexa returned to action closer to the end of the year with a slightly different version of his previous team, competing in several smaller tournaments with aim face and also in the European Championship 2014 with Bosnia & Herzegovina alongside players like Faruk “⁠pita⁠” Pita and Benjamin “⁠BENDJI⁠” Söderena. A few months later, he finally took up an offer to join MOUZ – whom he had previously rejected during his break from the scene over fears he wasn’t ready to play for an international team at the time.

Joining G2 Esports

2017 was a year of change for Nexa, who left MOUZ just two months into the season but not without giving the team a proper farewell as he averaged a sensational 1.48 rating at DreamHack Masters Las Vegas, his final tournament before the switch to FaZe. Freed from the in-game leadership shackles, Nexa immediately became the team’s star player, picking up a title in his second tournament under the North American organization, StarSeries Season 3, where he was also the MVP.

With reports of an impending move by Nexa to G2 already in full swing, FaZe enjoyed a sudden and unexpected burst of form in IEM New York, which they won convincingly after sweeping Vitality and OG in the playoffs. Nexa, who was top of the scoreboard in the three-map final (1.24 rating and 85.5 ADR), added to his MVP collection after putting up some year-high numbers, including a 1.28 rating, a 1.38 Impact rating, and 74.9% KAST.

Initial Days With G2 Esports

Nexa slotted into G2 seamlessly, but the team was unable to contend for titles in their first months with the Serbian player. He hit the ground running with a 1.24 rating as G2 topped a very tricky BLAST Premier Fall Series group that also included FURIA, MIBR, and Astralis, and played a key role in the team’s semi-final run in IEM Beijing-Haidian, in which he earned his final EVP award of the year with some respectable numbers, including a 1.36 Impact rating and a year-high 90.5 ADR.

After sitting out the IEM tournament, François “⁠AmaNEk⁠” Delaunay returned to the lineup for the final two events of the year, in which G2 looked somewhat sluggish, finishing 9th-12th in DreamHack Masters Winter and 5th-6th in the BLAST Premier Fall Finals. Despite being the team’s best performer in both competitions with ratings 10% higher than the squad’s average, Nexa was fairly underwhelming compared to his usual high standards, especially in the BLAST competition, in which he put up some of his worst numbers of the year (1.04 rating, 79.1 ADR and 64.3% KAST).
